'''Spotify''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|p|ɒ|t|ɪ|f|aɪ}}; {{IPA-sv|ˈspɔ̂tːɪfaj|lang}}) is a [[proprietary software|proprietary]] Swedish<ref name="spotify1">{{cite web|url=https://www.spotify.com/us/about-us/contact/ |title=Contact |publisher=Spotify |access-date=20 February 2022}}</ref> [[Streaming media|audio streaming]] and media services provider founded on 23 April 2006 by [[Daniel Ek]] and [[Martin Lorentzon]].<ref>{{cite web|date=14 October 2016|title=Spotify UK revenues surge to almost £190m as mobile subscriptions take off|url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/oct/14/spotify-uk-revenues-surge-to-almost-190m-as-mobile-subscriptions-take-off|access-date=6 August 2021|website=The Guardian|language=en}}</ref> It is one of the largest music streaming service providers, with over 456 million monthly [[active users]], including 195 million paying subscribers, as of September 2022.<ref name=QFR /><ref name="Spotify company info2">{{cite web|date=2 February 2022|title=Company Info|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/|url-status=live|access-date=2 February 2022|website=Spotify For the Record}}</ref> Spotify is listed (through a [[Luxembourg City]]-domiciled [[holding company]], '''Spotify Technology S.A.'''<ref name="sec" />) on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in the form of [[American depositary receipt]]s.

Spotify offers [[Digital rights management|digital copyright restricted]] recorded music and [[podcast]]s, including more than 82 million songs, from record labels and media companies.<ref name="Spotify company info2" /> As a [[freemium]] service, basic features are free with advertisements and limited control, while additional features, such as offline listening and commercial-free listening, are offered via paid [[Subscription business model|subscriptions]]. Users can search for music based on [[Musician|artist]], [[album]], or [[Music genre|genre]], and can create, edit, and share [[playlist]]s.

Spotify is available in most of Europe, as well as Africa, the Americas, Asia and [[Oceania]], with a total availability in 184 markets.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Spotify|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/|access-date=10 January 2022|website=Spotify|language=en-US}}</ref>  The service is available on most devices including [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[Linux]] computers, [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphones and tablets, [[Home automation|smart home]] devices such as the [[Amazon Echo]] and [[Google Nest]] lines of products and [[digital media player]]s like [[Roku]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Music|url=https://channelstore.roku.com/details/19977/spotify|access-date=12 November 2018|website=Roku Channel Store|publisher=Roku}}</ref>

Unlike physical or download sales, which pay artists a fixed price per song or album sold, Spotify pays [[royalties]] based on the number of artist streams as a proportion of total songs streamed. It distributes approximately 70% of its total revenue to rights holders (often [[record label]]s), who then pay artists based on individual agreements.<ref name=":22">{{Cite news|last=Sehgal|first=Kabir|date=26 January 2018|title=Spotify and Apple Music should become record labels so musicians can make a fair living|work=CNBC|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/26/how-spotify-apple-music-can-pay-musicians-more-commentary.html|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref> According to [[Ben Sisario]] of ''[[The New York Times]],'' approximately 13,000 out of seven million artists (0.19%) on Spotify generated $50,000 or more in payments in 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ovide|first=Shira|date=22 March 2021|title=Streaming Saved Music. Artists Hate It.|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/22/technology/streaming-music-economics.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/22/technology/streaming-music-economics.html |archive-date=28 December 2021 |url-access=limited|access-date=26 March 2021|issn=0362-4331}}{{cbignore}}</ref>
{{Toclimit|3}}

== History ==
[[File:Daniel Ek addressing Spotify staff.jpg|thumb|Daniel Ek addressing Spotify staff in 2010]]
Spotify was founded in 2006 in [[Stockholm]], Sweden,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20180302/the-story-of-spotify-swedens-controversial-king-of-music-streaming|newspaper=The Local Sweden|date=2 March 2018|title=The story of Spotify: Sweden's controversial king of music streaming
|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref> by [[Daniel Ek]], former [[Chief technology officer|CTO]] of [[Stardoll]], and Martin Lorentzon, co-founder of [[Tradedoubler]].<ref name="Parsons">{{cite web|title=History of Spotify: how the Swedish streaming company changed the music industry|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/history-spotify-how-swedish-streaming-12291542|last=Parsons|first=Jeff|date=3 April 2018|website=mirror|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How Spotify's college-dropout founder became a self-made millionaire at 23 — and a billionaire at 35|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/04/spotify-ceo-daniel-ek-is-a-billionaire-after-ipo.html|last=Huddleston|first=Tom Jr.|date=4 April 2018|website=CNBC|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref> According to Ek, the company's title was initially misheard from a name shouted by Lorentzon. Later they thought out a [[portmanteau]] of "spot" and "identify".<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify's Daniel Ek: The Most Important Man In Music|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenbertoni/2012/01/04/spotifys-daniel-ek-the-most-important-man-in-music/|last=Bertoni|first=Steven|website=Forbes|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref>

=== Early international launches ===
[[File:Spotify HQ.jpg|thumb|Former Spotify headquarters in Stockholm]]
In February 2010, Spotify opened public registration for the free service tier in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Parsons" /> Registrations surged following the release of the mobile service, leading Spotify to halt registration for the free service in September, returning the UK to an invitation-only policy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify reintroduces waiting list, nudges you to paying|url=https://www.theregister.com/2009/09/11/spotify_signups/|website=www.theregister.com|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref>

Spotify launched in the United States in July 2011, and offered a six-month, ad-supported trial period, during which new users could listen to an unlimited amount of music for free. In January 2012, the free trial periods began to expire, and limited users to ten hours of streaming each month and five plays per song.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify early adopters will soon lose unlimited listening on free accounts|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/1/6/2688250/spotify-free-account-restriction-10-hours-per-month|last=D'Orazio|first=Dante|date=6 January 2012|website=The Verge|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref> Using PC streaming, you would see a similar structure to what we see today,{{clarify|date=May 2022}} with a listener being able to play songs freely, but with ads every 4-7 songs depending on listening duration. Later that same year, in March, Spotify removed all limits on the free service tier indefinitely, including mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify to continue to let US users stream music for free|url=https://nypost.com/2012/03/29/spotify-to-continue-to-let-us-users-stream-music-for-free/|last=Report|first=Post Staff|date=29 March 2012|website=New York Post|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref>

In April 2016, Ek and Lorentzon wrote an open letter to Swedish politicians, demanding action in three areas that they claimed hindered the company's ability to recruit top talent as Spotify grows, including access to flexible housing, better education in the programming and development fields, and stock options. Ek and Lorentzon wrote that to continue competing in a global economy, politicians needed to respond with new policies, or else thousands of Spotify jobs would be moved from Sweden to the United States.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hazel |last=Sheffield |title=Spotify's threats to leave Sweden spur startup protest in Stockholm |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/spotifys-threats-to-leave-sweden-spur-startup-protest-in-stockholm-a6986431.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220524/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/spotifys-threats-to-leave-sweden-spur-startup-protest-in-stockholm-a6986431.html |archive-date=24 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |website=[[The Independent]] |date=15 April 2016 |access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref>

In February 2017, Spotify announced expansion of its United States operations in [[Lower Manhattan]], New York City, at [[4 World Trade Center]], adding approximately 1,000 new jobs and retaining 832 existing positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/16/17/spotify-expands-with-world-trade-center-move|title=Spotify expands with World Trade Center move|publisher=Agence France-Presse via ABS-CBN|date=15 February 2017|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> The company's US headquarters are located in New York City's [[Flatiron District]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Tanza |last=Loudenback |title=Step inside Spotify's New York City office, where you'll find an airy roof deck, cold brew coffee, and a secret recording studio |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-office-tour-2016-7 |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=25 July 2016 |access-date=19 February 2017}}</ref>

On 14 November 2018, the company announced a total of 13 new markets in the [[MENA]] region, including the creation of a new Arabic hub and several playlists.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 November 2021 |title=Spotify expands to Iraq and Libya |work=Arab News |url=https://arab.news/naj9n}}</ref>

=== Other developments ===
==== Streaming records ====
{{Main|List of most-streamed artists on Spotify}}
In October 2015, "[[Thinking Out Loud]]" by [[Ed Sheeran]] became the first song to pass 500 million streams.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Natalie |last=Weiner |title=Ed Sheeran's 'Thinking Out Loud' Becomes First Song to Hit 500 Million Spotify Streams |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6723002/ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-spotify-500-million-streams |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=12 October 2015 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> A month later, Spotify announced that "[[Lean On]]" by [[Major Lazer]] and [[DJ Snake]] featuring [[MØ]] was its most-streamed song of all time with over 525 million streams worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leaning power: Spotify names its most streamed track of all time |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/12/spotify-most-streamed-track-all-time-major-lazer-lean-on |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2015 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, [[Rihanna]] overtook [[Justin Bieber]] to become the biggest artist on Spotify, with 31.3 million monthly active listeners.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Ingham |title=The biggest artist on Spotify is a shareholder in Tidal |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/biggest-artist-spotify-shareholder-tidal |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=7 April 2016 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, Rihanna was overtaken by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] with 31.85 million total streams.<ref>{{cite web |first=Rhian |last=Jones |title=Drake is Spotify's most popular artist in history ... and right now |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-is-spotifys-most-popular-artist-in-history-and-right-now/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=18 May 2016 |access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> In December 2016, Drake's just-under 36 million monthly listeners were overtaken by the [[The Weeknd|Weeknd]]'s 36.068 million.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Ingham |title=Drake finally loses his Spotify crown to record-breaking The Weeknd |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-finally-loses-his-crown-on-spotifys-to-record-breaking-the-weeknd/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=1 December 2016 |access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> Later that same month, Drake's song "[[One Dance]]" became the first song to hit one billion streams on Spotify.<ref>{{cite web |first=Hugh |last=McIntyre |title=Drake's ''One Dance'' Is The First Song To Hit 1 Billion Plays On Spotify |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2016/12/16/drakes-one-dance-is-the-first-song-to-hit-1-billion-plays-on-spotify/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=16 December 2016 |access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Gil |last=Kaufman |title=Drake's ''One Dance'' Is First Song to Reach 1 Billion Plays on Spotify |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7625179/drake-one-dance-spotify-first-1-billion-plays |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=16 December 2016 |access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> Upon its release in August 2017, the single "[[Look What You Made Me Do]]" by [[Taylor Swift]] earned over eight million streams within 24 hours, breaking the record for the most single-day streams for a track.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apnews.com/54b87ebc88bd4565bd3bb1622970e6d9 |title=Taylor Swift sets records for Spotify streams and platforms, YouTube views |date=26 August 2017 |website=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref> On 19 June 2018, [[XXXTentacion]]'s hit single "[[Sad!]]" broke Swift's single-day streaming record, amassing 10.4 million streams the day after he was [[Killing of XXXTentacion|fatally shot]] in Florida.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8461986/xxxtentacion-spotify-streaming-record-day-taylor-swift|title=XXXTentacion Breaks Taylor Swift's Single-Day Streaming Record on Spotify |magazine=Billboard|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>

==== User growth ====
In March 2011, Spotify announced a customer base of 1 million paying subscribers across Europe,<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify hits milestone with 1 million subscribers |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-12676327 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC|date=8 March 2011 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> and by September 2011, the number of paying subscribers had doubled to two million.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jennifer |last=Van Grove |title=Spotify Surpasses 2 Million Paying Subscribers |url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/21/spotify-2-million-subscribers/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=21 September 2011 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> In August 2012, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported 15 million active users, four million being paying Spotify subscribers.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Josh |last=Sanburn |title=Spotify is Growing — But Why Isn't It Growing Faster? |url=http://business.time.com/2012/08/16/spotify-is-growing-but-the-idea-of-music-ownership-is-holding-it-back/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=16 August 2012 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> User growth continued, reaching 20 million total active users, including five million paying customers globally and one million paying customers in the United States, in December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Harrison |last=Weber |title=Spotify announces 5M+ paid subscribers globally, 1M paid in US, 20M total active users, 1B playlists |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2012/12/06/spotify-announces/ |website=The Next Web |date=6 December 2012 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> By March 2013, the service had 24 million active users, six million being paying subscribers,<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Sloan |title=Spotify: Growing like mad, yet so far to go |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-growing-like-mad-yet-so-far-to-go/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=29 May 2014 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> which grew to 40 million users (including ten million paying) in May 2014,<ref>{{cite web |first=Joshua |last=Brustein |title=Spotify Hits 10 Million Paid Users. Now Can It Make Money? |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-05-21/why-spotify-and-the-streaming-music-industry-cant-make-money |website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=22 May 2014 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> 60 million users (including 15 million paying) in December 2014, 75 million users (20 million paying) in June 2015, 30 million paying subscribers in March 2016,<ref>{{cite web |first=Micah |last=Singleton |title=Spotify hits 30 million subscribers |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/21/11220398/spotify-hits-30-million-subscribers |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=21 March 2016 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> 40 million paying subscribers in September 2016,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Kahn |title=Spotify hits 40 million paid subscriber milestone, outpacing Apple Music's growth |url=https://9to5mac.com/2016/09/14/spotify-40-million-subscribers/ |website=9to5Mac |date=14 September 2016 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> and 100 million total users in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web |first=Madhumita |last=Murgia |title=Spotify crosses 100&nbsp;m users |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/06/20/spotify-crosses-100m-users/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/06/20/spotify-crosses-100m-users/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=20 June 2016 |access-date=7 November 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In April 2020, Spotify reached 133 million premium users.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Gains 6 Million Paid Subscribers in Q1 as COVID-19 Disrupts Listening Patterns|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/spotify-q1-2020-gains-6-million-subscribers-coronavirus-1234592814/|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=29 April 2020|website=Variety|access-date=31 May 2020}}</ref> In countries affected by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], Spotify registered a fall in users in late February, but it has seen a recovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify's subscribers, usage surge amid coronavirus outbreak|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/29/spotify-spot-earnings-q1-2020.html|date=29 April 2020|website=CNBC|access-date=30 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2022, Spotify had 182 million premium subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Q1 2022 financials reveal 182m subscribers and 422m active users - Music Ally |url=https://musically.com/2022/04/27/spotify-q1-2022-financials/ |access-date=2022-07-27}}</ref> At the end of Q2 2022, Spotify reported 188 million paying subscribers and 433 million total users.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Porter |first=Jon |date=2022-07-27 |title=Spotify's subscribers rise to 188M amid podcasting setbacks |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/27/23280283/spotify-q2-2022-earnings-podcasting-audiobooks |access-date=2022-07-27 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref>

==== Premium-exclusive albums ====
The ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported in March 2017 that, as part of its efforts to renegotiate new licensing deals with music labels, Spotify and major record labels had agreed that Spotify would restrict some newly released albums to its Premium tier, with Spotify receiving a reduction in royalty fees to do so. Select albums would be available only on the Premium tier for a period of time, before general release. The deal "may be months away from being finalized, but Spotify is said to have cleared this particular clause with major record labels".<ref>{{cite web |first1=Nick |last1=Statt |first2=Micah |last2=Singleton |title=Spotify will restrict some albums to its paid tier |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/16/14950492/spotify-premium-free-tier-restricting-album-releases-ipo |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=16 March 2017 |access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Parker |last=Wilhelm |title=Spotify may soon require a Premium account to listen to certain albums |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/spotify-may-soon-require-a-premium-account-to-listen-to-certain-albums |website=[[TechRadar]]  |date=16 March 2017 |access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Summers |title=Spotify might delay album releases for 'free' users |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/16/spotify-might-delay-album-releases-for-free-users/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |date=16 March 2017 |access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref> New reports in April confirmed that Spotify and [[Universal Music Group]] had reached an agreement to allow artists part of Universal to limit their new album releases to the Premium service tier for a maximum of two weeks. Spotify CEO Daniel Ek commented that "We know that not every album by every artist should be released the same way, and we've worked hard with UMG to develop a new, flexible release policy. Starting today, Universal artists can choose to release new albums on premium only for two weeks, offering subscribers an earlier chance to explore the complete creative work, while the singles are available across Spotify for all our listeners to enjoy".<ref>{{cite web |first=Micah |last=Singleton |title=Spotify Premium users will get some albums two weeks before free users |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/4/15177004/spotify-premium-two-week-exclusive-albums-licensing-universal-music-group |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=4 April 2017 |access-date=5 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Titcomb |title=Spotify to restrict albums to paying subscribers for first time |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/04/spotify-restrict-albums-paying-subscribers-first-time/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/04/spotify-restrict-albums-paying-subscribers-first-time/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=4 April 2017 |access-date=5 April 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Hern |title=Spotify to host top stars' albums for premium subscribers only |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/apr/04/spotify-universal-albums-premium-subscribers-only |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 April 2017 |access-date=5 April 2017}}</ref> It was announced later in April that this type of agreement would be extended to [[Indie music scene|indie]] artists signed to the [[Merlin Network]] agency.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Marc |last=Schneider |title=Following Universal Deal, Spotify Locks Down Indies in Long-Term Licensing Pact With Merlin |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7767810/spotify-merlin-licensing-agreement-indies |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nathan |last=Ingraham |title=Spotify lets thousands of indie labels limit free streaming |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/20/spotify-merlin-records-limited-free-streaming/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=20 April 2017}}</ref>

==== Direct public offering ====
Spotify went public on the [[stock market]] in April 2018 using a [[direct public offering]] rather than an [[initial public offering]]. This approach is not intended to raise fresh capital, but to let investors get their returns.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43235317|title=Is Spotify really worth $23bn?|date=1 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/28/16846064/spotify-ipo-public-offering-announced-music-streaming|title=Spotify files to go public as it discloses subscriber growth and heavy losses|work=The Verge|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/28/spotify-files-for-ipo.html|title=Spotify files to go public, lost $1.5 billion last year|last=Castillo|first=Michelle|date=28 February 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref> [[Morgan Stanley]] is the company's slated advisor on the matter.<ref name=":1" />

After making its debut on the New York Stock Exchange on 3 April 2018, [[CNBC]] reported that Spotify opened at $165.90, more than 25% above its reference price of $132.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/03/spotify-spot-ipo-stock-starts-trading-on-the-nyse.html|title=Spotify loses some of its initial heat as it drops from its opening price of $165.90|last=Salinas|first=Sara|date=3 April 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref>

==== 2020 hacking incident ====
On 3 July 2020, [[Computer security|cybersecurity]] firm VPNMentor discovered a database containing 380 million individual records, including the logins and passwords of Spotify users.<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Spotify Targeted in Potential Fraud Scheme |url=https://www.vpnmentor.com/blog/report-spotify-scam/ |work=vpnMentor |date=24 November 2020 }}</ref> The database was thought to be evidence of an impending [[credential stuffing]] [[cyberattack]] targeting Spotify<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Mike |title=Thousands of Spotify accounts hacked – here's what you need to know |url=https://www.techradar.com/news/thousands-of-spotify-accounts-hacked-heres-what-you-need-to-know |work=TechRadar |date=24 November 2020}}</ref> as it contained the credentials of up to 350,000 compromised user accounts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Owaida |first1=Amer |title=Up to 350,000 Spotify accounts hacked in credential stuffing attacks |url=https://www.welivesecurity.com/2020/11/24/350000-spotify-accounts-hacked-credential-stuffing-attacks/ |work=WeLiveSecurity |date=24 November 2020}}</ref> In response to the attack, Spotify issued a rolling reset of passwords for affected accounts in November 2020.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Woodard |title=300,000 Spotify Accounts Reportedly Hacked |url=https://screenrant.com/spotify-accounts-data-stolen-major-hack-explained/ |work=ScreenRant |date=26 November 2020}}</ref>

==== Acquisitions and exclusivity deals ====
In May 2013, Spotify acquired music discovery app Tunigo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2013/05/03/spotify-acquires-music-discovery-app-tunigo-a-spotify-powered-songza-competitor/|title=Spotify Acquires Music Discovery App Tunigo, A Spotify-Powered Songza Competitor|date=3 May 2013 }}</ref> In March 2014, they acquired [[The Echo Nest]], a music intelligence company.<ref>{{cite web |first=Darrell |last=Etherington |title=Spotify Acquires The Echo Nest, Gaining Control Of The Music DNA Company That Powers Its Rivals |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/03/06/spotify-acquires-the-echo-nest/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=6 March 2014 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquired-echo-nest-just-e50m/ | title=Turns Out Spotify Acquired The Echo Nest For Just €50M| date=10 May 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, Spotify announced they had acquired Seed Scientific, a data science consulting firm and [[analytics]] company. In a comment to [[TechCrunch]], Spotify said that Seed Scientific's team would lead an advanced analytics unit within the company, focused on developing data services.<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Spotify Buys Beats' Analytics Provider Seed Scientific |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/pulling-the-data-rug-out-from-under-apple/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=24 June 2015 |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jonathan |last=Vanian |title=Why Spotify just bought a data science startup |url=http://fortune.com/2015/06/24/spotify-data-acquisition/ |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] . |date=24 June 2015 |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, they acquired social and messaging startups Cord Project and Soundwave,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2016/01/20/spotify-buys-cord-project-and-soundwave/|title=Spotify Buys Cord Project And Soundwave To Expand Messaging And Social Features|date=20 January 2016 }}</ref> followed in April 2016 by CrowdAlbum, a "startup that collects photos and videos of performances shared on social networks," and would "enhance the development of products that help artists understand, activate, and monetize their audiences".<ref>{{cite web |first=Joshua |last=Goldman |title=Spotify snaps up photo-video aggregator for concertgoers |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-snaps-up-crowdalbum-photo-and-video-aggregator-for-concertgoers/ |website=CNET |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=27 April 2016 |access-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> In November 2016, Spotify acquired Preact, a "cloud-based platform and service developed for companies that operate on subscription models which helps reduce churn and build up their subscriber numbers".<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify acquires Preact to fuel its subscription business |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/11/02/spotify-acquires-preact-to-boost-its-subscriber-story/ |publisher=Techcrunch |date=2 November 2016 |access-date=15 September 2020}}</ref>

In March 2017, Spotify acquired [[Sonalytic]], an audio detection startup, for an undisclosed amount of money. Spotify stated that Sonalytic would be used to improve the company's personalized playlists, better match songs with compositions, and improve the company's publishing data system.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Spotify acquires audio detection startup Sonalytic |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/spotify-acquires-audio-detection-startup-sonalytic/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=7 March 2017 |access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref> Later that month, Spotify also acquired MightyTV, an app connected to television streaming services, including [[Netflix]] and [[HBO Go]], that recommends content to users. Spotify intended to use MightyTV to improve its advertising efforts on the free tier of service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Ingham |title=Spotify acquires MightyTV. Can its founder fix Daniel Ek's advertising woes? |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-mightytv-can-its-founder-fix-daniel-eks-advertising-woes/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=27 March 2017 |access-date=5 May 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, they acquired Mediachain, a [[blockchain]] startup that had been developing a [[Decentralized computing|decentralized database]] system for managing attribution, and other [[metadata]] for media.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Spotify acquires blockchain startup Mediachain to solve music's attribution problem |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquires-blockchain-startup-mediachain-to-solve-musics-attribution-problem/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=26 April 2017 |access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Rob |last=LeFebvre |title=Spotify's latest move shows it's trying to get royalties right |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquisition-royalties/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL|date=26 April 2017 |access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref> This was followed in May 2017 with the acquisition of [[artificial intelligence]] startup Niland, which uses technology to improve personalisation and recommendation features for users.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Russell |title=Spotify buys AI startup Niland to develop its music personalization and recommendations |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-ai-startup-niland/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=18 May 2017 |access-date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Novet |title=Spotify just bought an AI startup to help it stay ahead of Apple Music |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-niland-french-ai-music-startup.html |website=CNBC |publisher=[[NBCUniversal News Group]] |date=18 May 2017 |access-date=20 May 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Spotify acquired [[Soundtrap]], an online music studio startup.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sarah |last1=Perez |first2=Ingrid |last2=Lunden |title=Spotify acquires online music studio Soundtrap as it goes after creators |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-online-music-studio-soundtrap/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=17 November 2017 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Swapna |last=Krishna |title=Spotify acquires Soundtrap, an online music recording studio |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-soundtrap-music-production-studio/ |website=Engadget |publisher=Oath Inc. |date=17 November 2017 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref>

On 12 April 2018, Spotify acquired the music licensing platform Loudr.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/12/spotify-acquires-music-licensing-platform-loudr/|title=Spotify acquires music licensing platform Loudr|last=Perez|first=Sarah|website=techcrunch.com|date=12 April 2018 |access-date=13 April 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, Spotify bought the exclusive rights to ''[[The Joe Budden Podcast]]'' and expanded the show to a twice-weekly schedule.<ref name="spotify-08-18">{{cite web |title='The Joe Budden Podcast' Lands Exclusive Partnership with Spotify |url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2018-08-22/the-joe-budden-podcast-lands-exclusive-partnership-with-spotify |website=Spotify Newsroom |access-date=June 29, 2019 |date=August 22, 2018 |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604210722/http://newsroom.spotify.com/2018-08-22/the-joe-budden-podcast-lands-exclusive-partnership-with-spotify/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 6 February 2019, Spotify acquired the podcast networks [[Gimlet Media]] and Anchor FM Inc., with the goal of establishing themselves as a leading figure in podcasting.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kafka |first=Peter |title=Spotify has bought two podcast startups and it wants to buy more |url=https://www.recode.net/2019/2/6/18213456/spotify-podcast-gimlet-anchor-q4-results |access-date=7 February 2019 |work=Recode |date=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Warren |first1=Tom |title=Spotify gets serious about podcasts with two acquisitions |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/6/18213462/spotify-podcasts-gimlet-anchor-acquisition |access-date=7 February 2019 |work=The Verge |date=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/02/06/spotify-doubles-down-on-podcasts/|title=Spotify buys Gimlet and Anchor in podcast push, earmarks $500M for more deals|last=Russell|first=Jon|date=6 February 2019|website=TechCrunch|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> On 26 March 2019, Spotify announced they would acquire another podcast network, [[Parcast]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify acquires another podcast network to keep building its original show catalog|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/26/18282301/spotify-podcasts-parcast-acquisition-gimlet-media-anchor |website=The Verge|date=26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/26/spotify-acquires-true-crime-studio-parcast-to-expand-its-original-podcast-content/|title=Spotify acquires true crime studio Parcast to expand its original podcast content|website=TechCrunch|date=26 March 2019 |access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref> On 12 September 2019, Spotify acquired [[SoundBetter]], a music production marketplace for people in the music industry to collaborate on projects, and distribute music tracks for licensing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/09/12/spotify-acquires-soundbetter-an-online-marketplace-for-sound-engineers-and-producers/|title=Spotify acquires SoundBetter, a music production marketplace, for an undisclosed sum|website=TechCrunch|date=12 September 2019 |access-date=12 September 2019}}</ref> On November 19, 2019, Spotify announced the acquisition of the exclusive rights to ''[[The Last Podcast on the Left]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/last-podcast-left-moving-exclusively-spotify-1256236|title='Last Podcast on the Left' Moving Exclusively to Spotify|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=November 19, 2019|language=en|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>

On 5 February 2020, Spotify announced its intent to acquire [[Bill Simmons]]' sports and pop culture blog and podcast network [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/business/media/spotify-the-ringer-bill-simmons.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205141009/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/business/media/spotify-the-ringer-bill-simmons.html |archive-date=2020-02-05 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Spotify Is Buying The Ringer|last1=Robertson|first1=Katie|date=5 February 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=5 February 2020|last2=Scheiber|first2=Noam|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/02/05/spotify-is-buying-the-ringer-to-boost-its-sports-podcast-content/|title=Spotify is buying The Ringer to boost its sports podcast content|website=TechCrunch|date=5 February 2020 |access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>  On 19 May 2020, Spotify acquired exclusive rights to stream the popular podcast ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'' beginning in September of that year, under an agreement valued at around US$100 million''.<ref name="Spangler">{{cite web|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=May 19, 2020|title=Joe Rogan Will Bring His Podcast Exclusively to Spotify|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/joe-rogan-experience-spotify-podcast-exclusive-1234610885/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200519204108/https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/joe-rogan-experience-spotify-podcast-exclusive-1234610885/|archive-date=May 19, 2020|access-date=May 19, 2020|website=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|date=2021-07-01|title=Joe Rogan Is Too Big to Cancel|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/01/business/joe-rogan.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210701150506/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/01/business/joe-rogan.html |archive-date=2021-07-01 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=2022-01-29|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>''

In November 2020, Spotify announced plans to acquire [[Megaphone (podcasting)|Megaphone]] from [[The Slate Group]] for {{USD|235 million}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/10/21557458/spotify-megaphone-podcast-streaming-ad-insertion|title=Spotify is acquiring podcast hosting company Megaphone for $235 million|first=Ashley|last=Carman|date=10 November 2020|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=10 November 2020}}</ref> In March 2021, Spotify acquired app developer Betty Labs and their live social audio app, Locker Room,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fischer|first=Sara|date=31 March 2021|title=Spotify enters live social audio with acquisition of Locker Room|url=https://www.axios.com/spotify-betty-labs-locker-room-52550d15-3c05-48ed-b924-a9404c31901b.html|url-status=live|access-date=5 April 2021|website=Axios|language=en}}</ref> On May 12, 2021. ''[[Armchair Expert]]'' announced on [[Instagram]] that the podcast would be available exclusively on Spotify beginning July 1, saying they would continue to maintain the same creative control over the show after the move.<ref>{{cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=12 May 2021 |title=Dax Shepard Is Moving His Podcast Exclusively to Spotify This Summer |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/dax-shepard-podcast-spotify-1234971432/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ArmchairExpPod |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/COyIAl1p4pY/  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/instagram/armchairexppod/2572153562182683224 |archive-date=2021-12-25 |url-access=registration|website=Instagram |access-date=2021-05-14}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Locker Room was rebranded in June 2021 as [[Spotify Greenroom]], and turned into a [[Clubhouse (app)|Clubhouse]] competitor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2021/06/16/spotify-launches-its-live-audio-app-and-clubhouse-rival-spotify-greenroom/|title=Spotify launches its live audio app and Clubhouse rival, Spotify Greenroom|date=16 June 2021 }}</ref> The same month, Spotify acquired Podz, a podcast discovery startup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/06/17/spotify-acquires-podz-a-podcast-discovery-app/|title = Spotify acquires Podz, a podcast discovery platform| date=17 June 2021 }}</ref> Also the same month, Spotify bought the exclusive rights to the ''[[Call Her Daddy]]'' podcast.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-call-her-daddy-alex-cooper-exclusive-1234996840/|title=Spotify Clinches $60M-Plus Deal With Alex Cooper for 'Call Her Daddy' Podcast, Yanking It Away From Barstool|first1=Todd|last1=Spangler|date=June 15, 2021|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=June 18, 2021|archive-date=June 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210618153312/https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-call-her-daddy-alex-cooper-exclusive-1234996840/|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2021, Spotify acquired audiobook company Findaway, including its publishing imprint OrangeSky Audio.<ref>{{cite web|date=12 November 2021|title=Spotify Acquires Audiobook Company Findaway|url=https://www.androidheadlines.com/2021/11/spotify-acquires-audiobook-company.html|access-date=21 December 2021|website=Android Headlines|language=en-US}}</ref> In December 2021, Spotify acquired Whooshkaa, a podcast tech company that develops specialized technology that allows radio broadcasters to easily turn their existing audio content into on-demand podcast programming.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/12/16/spotify-acquires-podcast-tech-company-whooshkaa-which-turns-radio-broadcasts-into-on-demand-audio/ | title=Spotify acquires podcast tech company Whooshkaa which turns radio broadcasts into on-demand audio | date=16 December 2021 }}</ref>

In February 2022, Spotify acquired Chartable and Podsights. Both are podcast advertising companies.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=2022-02-16 |title=Spotify is acquiring two major podcast tech platforms |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/2/16/22937826/spotify-podsights-chartable-acquisitions-podcast-marketing-platforms |access-date=2022-03-22 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref> In 2022, Spotify Greenroom rebranded as [[Spotify Greenroom|Spotify Live]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-23 |title=Spotify rebranding its live social audio app |url=https://adage.com/article/marketing-news-strategy/spotify-rebranding-its-live-social-audio-app/2407731 |access-date=2022-03-23 |website=Ad Age |language=en}}</ref> 
In June 2022, Spotify acquired Sonantic, a synthetic voice and video developer.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://voicebot.ai/2022/06/13/spotify-acquires-synthetic-voice-startup-sonantic/ | title=Spotify Acquires Synthetic Voice Startup Sonantic | date=13 June 2022 }}</ref> In July 2022, Spotify acquired Heardle, a [[Wordle]]-inspired music trivia game, for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify acquired Heardle, the Wordle-like music game |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2022/07/12/spotify-acquired-heardle-wordle-music-game/ |access-date=2022-07-15 |website=TechCrunch |date=12 July 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shapiro |first=Ariel |date=2022-07-12 |title=Spotify acquires music trivia game Heardle |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/12/23205078/spotify-heardle-acquisition-music-discovery-wordle-game |access-date=2022-07-15 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref> In October 2022, Spotify acquired the [[Dublin]]-based content moderation startup, Kinzen.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-06 |title=Spotify acquires Dublin-based content moderation startup Kinzen |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-dublin-based-content-moderation-startup-kinzen/ |access-date=2022-10-06 |website=Music Business Worldwide |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Company partnerships ====
In January 2015, [[Sony]] announced PlayStation Music, a new music service with Spotify as its exclusive partner. PlayStation Music incorporates the Spotify service into Sony's [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation 4]] gaming consoles, and [[Sony Xperia]] mobile devices. The service launched on 30 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Lempel |title=Spotify Launches on PlayStation Music Today |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2015/03/30/spotify-launches-on-playstation-music-today/ |publisher=Sony |date=30 March 2015 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> In March 2017, Spotify announced a partnership with the [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) conference for 2017, presenting specific content in special playlists through an SXSW hub in Spotify's apps. The integration also enabled Spotify within the SXSW GO app to help users discover and explore artists performing at the conference. Two more partnerships were announced in March; one with [[WNYC Studios]], and one with [[Waze]]. The WNYC Studios partnership brought various podcasts from WNYC to Spotify, including [[Note To Self]], [[On the Media]] and [[Here's the Thing]]. Spotify also announced that the third season of WNYC Studios' [[2 Dope Queens]] podcast would premiere with a two-week exclusivity period on the service on 21 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=Derrick |last=Rossignol |title=Spotify lands '2 Dope Queens' and other hit WNYC podcasts |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/13/spotify-lands-2-dope-queens-and-other-hit-wnyc-podcasts/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |date=13 March 2017 |access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref> The Waze partnership allows Waze app users to view directions to destinations within the Spotify app and access their Spotify playlists through the Waze app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Nieva |title=Spotify gives you driving directions through Waze |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-waze-driving-directions-playlist-integrations/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=14 March 2017 |access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref>

In October 2017, [[Microsoft]] announced that it would be ending its [[Groove Music]] streaming service by December, with all music from users transferring to Spotify as part of a new partnership.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Microsoft retires Groove Music service, partners with Spotify |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/2/16401898/microsoft-groove-music-pass-discontinued-spotify-partner |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=2 October 2017 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref> In December, Spotify and [[Tencent]]'s music arm, Tencent Music Entertainment (TME), agreed to swap stakes and make an investment in each other's music businesses.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Russell |title=Spotify and Tencent agree to swap stakes in their music businesses |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/08/spotify-tencent-share-swap/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=8 December 2017 |access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Sawers |title=Spotify and China's Tencent invest in each other as part of 'strategic collaboration' |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/08/spotify-and-chinas-tencent-invest-in-each-other-as-part-of-strategic-collaboration/ |website=[[VentureBeat]] |date=8 December 2017 |access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> As a result of this transaction, Spotify gained a 9% stake in TME with TME gaining a 7.5% stake in Spotify.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/28/tencent-music-spotify/|title=Tencent Music, Spotify's strategic partner in China, is valued at over $12B – TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|date=March 2018 |access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref>

In February 2018, Spotify integrated with the gaming-oriented voice chat service [[Discord (software)|Discord]] on desktop clients, allowing users to display their currently playing song as a rich presence on their profile, and invite other users with Spotify Premium to group "listening parties".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/1/16950076/discord-spotify-partnership-streaming-playlists-gaming-listening-habits|title=Please tell me Spotify's new partnership with Discord will fix its bad gamer playlists|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=1 February 2018|website=The Verge|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> In April, Spotify announced a discounted entertainment bundle with video-on-demand provider [[Hulu]], which included discounted rates for university students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/11/spotify-and-hulu-launch-a-discounted-entertainment-bundle-for-12-99-per-month/|title=Spotify and Hulu launch a discounted entertainment bundle for $12.99 per month|last=Perez|first=Sarah|date=11 April 2018|website=TechCrunch|access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>

In May 2020, Spotify teamed up with [[ESPN]] and [[Netflix]] to curate podcasts around their [[Michael Jordan]] documentary ''[[The Last Dance (miniseries)|The Last Dance]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Netflix and ESPN team up with Spotify to curate podcasts around their Michael Jordan documentary|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/1/21243927/netflix-espn-spotify-the-last-dance-michael-jordan-documentary-podcast|last=Carman|first=Ashley|date=1 May 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=3 May 2020}}</ref> and in September, Spotify signed a deal with [[Chernin Entertainment]] to produce movies and TV shows.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Strikes First-Look Deal To Adapt Podcasts As Movies And TV Shows|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/news/spotify-strikes-first-look-deal-adapt-podcasts-movies-and-tv/|access-date=25 September 2020|website=Movies}}</ref>

In 2022, Spotify became the official streaming partner of [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=CohenMarch 15 |first1=David |last2=2022 |title=Spotify to Become Main Partner, Official Audio Streaming Partner of FC Barcelona |url=https://www.adweek.com/social-marketing/spotify-to-become-main-partner-official-audio-streaming-partner-of-fc-barcelona/ |access-date=2022-03-23 |language=en-US}}</ref>

In May 2022, Spotify announced a partnership with the online game platform and game creation system the Roblox Corporation, the partnership saw Spotify as the first streaming brand to have a presence within the game with the launch of "Spotify Island".<ref>{{cite journal|date=3 May 2022|url= https://techcrunch.com/2022/05/03/spotify-becomes-first-music-streamer-to-launch-on-roblox/|title= Spotify becomes first music streamer to launch on Roblox|journal=Tech Crunch|access-date=3 May 2022|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Dispute with Apple ====
{{See also|Criticism of Apple Inc.#Spotify}}
In July 2015, Spotify launched an email campaign to urge its [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] subscribers to cancel their subscriptions and start new ones through its website, bypassing the 30% transaction fee for in-app purchases required for [[iOS]] applications by technology company [[Apple Inc.]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Welch |title=Spotify urges iPhone customers to stop paying through Apple's App Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/7/8/8913105/spotify-apple-app-store-email |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=8 July 2015 |access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref> A later update to the Spotify app on iOS was rejected by Apple, prompting Spotify's general counsel Horacio Gutierrez to write a letter to Apple's then-general counsel Bruce Sewell, stating: "This latest episode raises serious concerns under both U.S. and EU competition law. It continues a troubling pattern of behavior by Apple to exclude and diminish the competitiveness of Spotify on iOS and as a rival to [[Apple Music]], particularly when seen against the backdrop of Apple's previous anticompetitive conduct aimed at Spotify ... we cannot stand by as Apple uses the App Store approval process as a weapon to harm competitors."<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Kafka |title=Spotify says Apple won't approve a new version of its app because it doesn't want competition for Apple Music |url=http://www.recode.net/2016/6/30/12067578/spotify-apple-app-store-rejection |website=[[Recode]]  |date=30 June 2016 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref>

Sewell responded to the letter: "We find it troubling that you are asking for exemptions to the rules we apply to all developers and are publicly resorting to rumors and half-truths about our service." He also elaborated that "Our guidelines apply equally to all app developers, whether they are game developers, e-book sellers, video-streaming services or digital music distributors; and regardless of whether they compete against Apple. We did not alter our behavior or our rules when we introduced our own music streaming service or when Spotify became a competitor". Furthermore, he stated that "There is nothing in Apple's conduct that 'amounts to a violation of applicable antitrust laws.' Far from it. ... I would be happy to facilitate an expeditious review and approval of your app as soon as you provide us with something that is compliant with the App Store's rules".<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Paczkowski |title=Apple Slams Spotify For Asking For "Preferential Treatment" |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/johnpaczkowski/apple-fires-back-at-spotify-for-asking-for-preferential-trea |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701215735/https://www.buzzfeed.com/johnpaczkowski/apple-fires-back-at-spotify-for-asking-for-preferential-trea |website=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=1 July 2016 |archive-date=1 July 2016 |access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Oscar |last=Raymundo |title=Apple slams Spotify for criticizing the App Store as anti-competitive |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3090219/ios/spotify-lawyers-up-against-apple-for-rejecting-its-updated-ios-app.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=1 July 2016 |access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref>

In the following months, Spotify joined several other companies in filing a letter with the [[European Union]]'s [[antitrust]] body indirectly accusing Apple and [[Google]] of "abusing their 'privileged position' at the top of the market", by referring to "some" companies as having "transformed into 'gatekeepers' rather than 'gateways'".<ref>{{cite web |first=Mikey |last=Campbell |title=Spotify, others file EU complaint over Apple and Google app store practices |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/05/05/spotify-others-file-eu-complaint-over-apple-and-google-app-store-practices |website=AppleInsider |date=5 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chance |last=Miller |title=Spotify again accuses Apple of abusing its size & acting as a 'gatekeeper' |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/06/spotify-again-accuses-apple-of-abusing-its-size-acting-as-a-gatekeeper/ |website=9to5Mac |date=6 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref> The complaint led to the European Union announcing that it would prepare an initiative by the end of 2017 for a possible law addressing unfair competition practices.<ref>{{cite web |first=Julia |last=Fioretti |title=EU to tackle complaints over tech companies' trading practices |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-digital-idUSKBN18614K |work=Reuters |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |date=10 May 2017 |access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Lovejoy |title=EU planning a new law addressing 'unfair contractual clauses' following Spotify's complaint against Apple |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/10/eu-apple-spotify-complaint/ |website=9to5Mac |date=10 May 2017 |access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref>

Spotify released the first version of its [[Apple Watch]] app in November 2018, allowing playback control of the iPhone via the watch. Users can also choose which devices to play music on via Bluetooth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/11/spotify-officially-releases-first-version-of-its-apple-watch-app/|title=Spotify officially releases the first version of its Apple Watch app|work=Ars Technica|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref> In a further escalation of the dispute with Apple, on 13 March 2019, Spotify filed an antitrust complaint with the European Commission over unfair app store practices. Two days later, Apple responded, stating that the claim was misleading rhetoric and that Spotify wanted benefits of a free app without being a free app. Spotify responded with a statement calling Apple a monopolist and stated that they had only filed the complaint as Apple's actions hurt competition and consumers and clearly violated the law. It also said that Apple believed Spotify users on the app store were Apple's customers and not Spotify's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2019/03/16/spotify-calls-apple-monopolist/|title=Spotify on Apple's Response to App Store Dispute: 'Every Monopolist Will Suggest They Have Done Nothing Wrong'|last=Rossignol|first=Joe|website=www.macrumors.com|access-date=19 March 2019}}</ref>

Apple responded to Spotify's claims by counter-claiming that Spotify's market reach and user base would not have been possible without the Apple App Store platform. Additionally, Apple stated that they have attempted to work with Spotify to integrate the service better with Apple's products, such as [[Siri]] and Apple Watch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/03/addressing-spotifys-claims/|title=Addressing Spotify's Claims|website=Apple Newsroom|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> In 2019, under [[iOS 13]], it became possible to play Spotify music using Siri commands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bgr.com/2019/10/07/apple-vs-spotify-siri-integration-ios-13/|title=Apple just finally added Spotify integration to Siri in iOS 13|last=Meek|first=Andy|date=7 October 2019|website=BGR|access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>

Spotify was one of the first companies to support [[Epic Games]] in their [[Epic Games v. Apple|lawsuit against Apple]], which was filed after Epic also tried to bypass Apple's 30% fee for [[microtransactions]] in [[Fortnite]]. In September 2020, Spotify, Epic, and other companies founded [[The Coalition for App Fairness]], which aims for better conditions for the inclusion of apps in [[app store]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Amadeo|first=Ron|date=24 September 2020|title=Epic, Spotify, and others take on Apple with "Coalition for App Fairness"|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/09/epic-spotify-and-others-take-on-apple-with-coalition-for-app-fairness/|access-date=26 September 2020|website=Ars Technica}}</ref>

==== Dispute with Kakao Entertainment Corp. ====
On March 1, 2021, Spotify confirmed that its platform would no longer have access to music from artists represented by Kakao Entertainment. However, after talking it out and renewing the contracts between the two, Spotify later announced that they had reached an agreement with Kakao Entertainment, allowing their content to be available once again on the platform across the globe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-k-pop-kakao-licensing-dispute-1234927727/|title=Spotify and K-Pop Label Kakao Settle Licensing Dispute, Music Returning to Platform|date=10 March 2021}}</ref>

==== Functionality ====
In November 2021, Spotify hid the "shuffle" button for albums following a request by singer [[Adele]], arguing that tracks in albums are supposed to be played back in the order specified by the artist in order to "tell a story".<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-11-21 |title=Spotify hides shuffle button after Adele says albums should 'tell a story' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/nov/21/spotify-hides-shuffle-button-adele-albums-should-tell-a-story |access-date=2022-04-19 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref>

==== NFTs ====
In May 2022, Spotify began testing a feature that would allow select artists to promote their [[Non-fungible token|NFTs]] via their profiles. Some artists included in this initial test phase were [[Steve Aoki]] and [[The Wombats]].  The testing was very limited in nature and was only available on Spotify's Android app in the US.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Exclusive: Spotify tests letting artists promote NFTs on their profiles - Music Ally |url=https://musically.com/2022/05/13/spotify-artists-promote-nfts/ |access-date=2022-05-17}}</ref>

== Business model ==
Spotify operates under a [[freemium]] business model (basic services are free, while additional features are offered via paid subscriptions). Spotify generates revenue by selling premium streaming subscriptions to users and advertising placements to third parties. Some of the premium options users may choose from include individual, duo, family, and student.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Premium|url=http://www.spotify.com/us/premium/|access-date=2022-02-14|website=Spotify|language=en-US}}</ref>

In December 2013, the company launched a new website, "Spotify for Artists, " explaining its business model and revenue data. Spotify gets its content from major record labels as well as [[independent artist]]s and pays [[copyright]] holders [[royalties]] for streaming music. The company pays 70% of its total revenue to rights holders. Spotify for Artists states that the company does not have a fixed per-play rate; instead, it considers factors such as the user's home country and the individual artist's royalty rate. Rights holders received an average per-play payout between $.000029 and $.0084.<ref name="Spotify business">{{cite web |title=How is Spotify contributing to the music business? |url=http://www.spotifyartists.com/spotify-explained/ |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20141103193456/http://www.spotifyartists.com/spotify-explained/ |publisher=Spotify |archive-date=3 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Spotify offers an unlimited subscription package, close to the [[Open Music Model]] (OMM) estimated [[economic equilibrium]] for the recording industry.{{Citation needed|date=September 2020}} However, the incorporation of [[digital rights management]] (DRM) limitation<ref name="DRM">{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Orlowski |title=Spotify, DRM and the celestial jukebox |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/08/31/spotify_crypto |website=[[The Register]] |publisher=Situation Publishing |date=31 August 2009 |access-date=8 November 2016}}</ref> diverges from the OMM and competitors such as [[iTunes Store]] and [[Amazon Music]] that have dropped DRM.<ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Bobbie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jan/06/apple-drops-itunes-copy-protection |title=Apple drops DRM copy protection from millions of iTunes songs |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 January 2009 |access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Don |last=Reisinger |title=Warner Music Group drops DRM, joins Amazon |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/audio/warner-music-group-drops-drm-joins-amazon-180371 |website=[[TechRadar]]  |date=4 January 2008 |access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref>

In 2013, Spotify revealed that it paid artists an average of $0.007 per stream. ''[[Music Week]]'' editor Tim Ingham commented that the figure was not as "alarming" as it appeared, writing: "Unlike buying a CD or download, streaming is not a one-off payment. Hundreds of millions of streams of tracks are happening every day, which quickly multiplies the potential revenues on offer – and is a constant long-term source of income for artists."<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify reveals artists earn $0.007 per stream |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25217353 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 December 2013 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref>

