In March 2014, Spotify introduced a discounted Premium subscription tier for students in which students in the United States enrolled in a university pay half-price for a Premium subscription.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian Anthony |last=Hernandez |title=Spotify Slashes Subscription Prices for College Students |url=http://mashable.com/2014/03/25/spotify-premium-student-discount/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=25 March 2014 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the discount was expanded to 33 more countries.<ref>{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Dalton |title=Spotify's half-price plan for students comes to 33 more countries |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/19/spotifys-half-price-premium-for-students-33-more-countries/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=19 April 2017 |access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Luke |last=Lancaster |title=Students can now pick up Spotify Premium for half price |url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/students-can-now-pick-up-spotify-premium-for-half-price/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=19 April 2017 |access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref>

Spotify introduced a Family subscription in October 2014, which allows up to 5 family members to have a premium subscription.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Spotify Family lets you share a subscription from $14.99 per month |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/20/7013227/spotify-family-shared-premium-subscription-pricing-features |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=20 October 2014 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steve |last=O'Hear |title=Spotify Introduces Family Plan, Starting At $14.99 Per Month For Two Members |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/20/spotify-introduces-family-plan-starting-at-14-99-per-month-for-two-members/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=Oath Inc. |date=20 October 2014 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref> In May 2016, the limit was changed to 6 family members, and the price was reduced.<ref>{{cite web |first=Romain |last=Dillet |title=Spotify family plan is now cheaper, $14.99 for up to 6 people |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/23/spotify-family-plan-is-now-cheaper-14-99-for-up-to-6-people/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=Oath Inc. |date=23 May 2016 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref> The Family subscription provides access to [[Spotify Kids]].<ref name=":12">{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Dave|date=24 November 2021|title=How to sign up for Spotify's Family plan, the streaming service's membership for up to 6 people|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-family-plan|url-status=live|access-date=1 December 2021|website=[[Business Insider]]|language=en-US}}</ref>

In November 2018, Spotify announced it was opening up Spotify Connect to all of the users using its Free service, however, these changes still required products supporting Spotify Connect to support the latest [[software development kit]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Heater |title=Spotify Connect speakers will soon work with its free tier|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-speakers-will-soon-work-with-its-free-tier/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher= Oath Inc.|date=7 November 2018 |access-date=10 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Sawers |title=Spotify Connect for speakers opens to free users via a new SDK|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-opens-to-free-users-via-a-new-sdk-for-hardware-makers/ |website=[[Venturebeat]] |date=7 November 2018 |access-date=10 November 2018}}</ref>

In July 2020,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Guinness |first=Harry |title=What Is Spotify Duo, and Is It Right for You? |url=https://www.howtogeek.com/680795/what-is-spotify-duo-and-is-it-right-for-you/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706191004/https://www.howtogeek.com/680795/what-is-spotify-duo-and-is-it-right-for-you/ |archive-date=2022-07-06 |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=How-To Geek |language=en-US}}</ref> Spotify added another tier, Premium Duo.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Premium Duo |url=http://www.spotify.com/uk/duo/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706191353/https://www.spotify.com/uk/duo/ |archive-date=2022-07-06 |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=Spotify |language=en-GB}}</ref> This is aimed at couples and for $12.99 it lets up to 2 people (living at the same address) share a subscription.

In February 2021, Spotify announced their plans to introduce a HiFi subscription, to offer listening in [[high fidelity]], lossless sound quality. The rollout for the HiFi tier is yet to be announced.<ref name=":3" />

In August 2021, Spotify launched a test subscription tier called Spotify Plus. The subscription costs $0.99 and is supposed to be a combination of the free and premium tiers. Subscribers to this plan will still receive ads but will get the ability to listen to songs without shuffle mode and skip any number of tracks. The company reported that the tier conditions may change before its full launch.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Porter |title=Spotify is testing a less restrictive ad-supported tier costing $0.99 a month |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/3/22607203/spotify-plus-ad-supported-tier-unlimited-skips-on-demand-listening |website=The Verge |date=3 August 2021 |access-date=3 August 2021}}</ref> This might have been discontinued (at least in some regions) according to an email sent to a redditor.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-02-09 |title=Spotify is ending its Spotify Plus service. I hope that it just becomes the default free service now, otherwise I'm really going to miss on demand music streaming for $3 a month |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/truespotify/comments/sopj5h/spotify_is_ending_its_spotify_plus_service_i_hope/ |url-status=live |website=Reddit}}</ref>

=== Monetization ===
In 2008, just after launch, the company made a loss of 31.8 million Swedish kronor (US$4.4 million).<ref>{{cite web |first=Johan |last=Nylander |title=Spotify doubled its loss last year |url=http://www.swedishwire.com/business/751-spotify-doubled-its-loss-last-year |website=The Swedish Wire |date=17 August 2009 |access-date=7 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181238/http://www.swedishwire.com/business/751-spotify-doubled-its-loss-last-year|archive-date=3 March 2016}}</ref> In October 2010, ''[[Wired (website)|Wired]]'' reported that Spotify was making more money for labels in Sweden than any other retailer "online or off".<ref>{{cite web |first=Duncan |last=Geere |title=Spotify now top-tier music revenue source in Sweden |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2010-10/29/spotify-swedish-revenue |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030230717/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2010-10/29/spotify-swedish-revenue |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |date=29 October 2010 |archive-date=30 October 2010 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> Years after growth and expansion, a November 2012 report suggested strong momentum for the company. In 2011, it reported a near US$60 million net loss from revenue of $244 million, while it was expected to generate a net loss of $40 million from revenue of $500 million in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Eldon |title=Spotify Is Having A Good 2012: Revenues Could Reach $500M As It Expands The Digital Music Market |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/11/10/spotify-is-having-a-good-2012-revenues-could-reach-500m-as-it-expands-the-digital-music-market/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=10 November 2012 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> Another source of income was music purchases from within the app, however this service was removed in January 2013.<ref name="No purchase">{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Brian |title=Spotify is no longer offering new music download purchases to its users |url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/01/04/spotify-is-no-longer-offering-new-music-download-purchases-to-its-users/ |website=The Next Web |date=4 January 2013 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref>

In May 2016, Spotify announced "Sponsored Playlists", a monetisation opportunity in which brands can specify the audiences they have in mind, with Spotify matching the marketer with suitable music in a playlist.<ref>{{cite web |first=Marty |last=Swant |title=Spotify Will Now Let Brands Sponsor the Most Popular Playlists |url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/spotify-will-now-let-brands-sponsor-most-popular-playlists-171706/ |website=[[Adweek]] |publisher=Beringer Capital |date=26 May 2016 |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Maureen |last=Morrison |title=Spotify Opens Its Popular Playlists to Sponsors |url=http://adage.com/article/digital/spotify-expands-ad-formats-sponsored-playlists/304174/ |website=[[Advertising Age]]  |date=26 May 2016 |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref> That September, Spotify announced that it had paid a total of over $5 billion to the music industry.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Ingham |title=Spotify has already paid the music industry over $1.2bn this year |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-has-already-paid-the-music-business-1-2bn-this-year/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=29 September 2016 |access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, as part of renegotiated licenses with Universal Music Group and Merlin Network, Spotify's financial filings revealed its agreement to pay more than $2 billion in minimum payments over the next two years.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Kafka |title=Spotify has guaranteed to pay big music labels billions over the next two years |url=https://www.recode.net/2017/6/15/15807382/spotify-revenue-2016-financials-guarantee-payment-universal-merlin |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=15 June 2017 |access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Giles |last1=Turner |first2=Lucas |last2=Shaw |title=Spotify's Loss More Than Doubles Even as User Growth Surges |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-15/spotify-losses-widen-after-music-site-flags-accounting-errors |website=Bloomberg Technology |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=15 June 2017 |access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref>

{{As of|2017}}, Spotify was not yet a profitable company.<ref>{{cite web |first=Robert |last=Plummer |title=The clock is ticking for Spotify |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-38930699 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 February 2017 |access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref> Spotify's revenue for Q1 2020 amounted to €1.85 billion ($2 billion). A large part of this sum, €1.7 billion ($1.84 billion), came from Spotify Premium subscribers. Gross profit in the same quarter amounted to €472 million ($511 million), with an operating loss of €17 million ($18 million).<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Usage and Revenue Statistics (2020)|url=https://www.businessofapps.com/data/spotify-statistics/|date=20 December 2018|website=Business of Apps|access-date=14 May 2020}}</ref> Despite subscriber and podcasts growth, during Q2 of 2020, Spotify reported a loss of €356 million (€1.91 per share). The "deeper" loss came as a result of the company's tax debt to over one-third of its employees in Sweden.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-loss-deepens-despite-subscriber-podcast-growth-11596016801?mod=business_lead_pos6|title= Spotify Loss Deepens Despite Subscriber, Podcast Growth |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|last=Steele|first=Anne|date=29 July 2020|access-date=29 July 2020}}</ref>

==== Funding ====
In February 2010, Spotify received a small investment from [[Founders Fund]], where board member [[Sean Parker]] was recruited to assist Spotify in "winning the labels over in the world's largest music market".<ref>{{cite web |first1=Tim |last1=Bradshaw |first2=Joseph |last2=Menn |title=Spotify-MOG battle heats up |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7a289b4e-249b-11df-8be0-00144feab49a |website=[[Financial Times]] |publisher=[[The Nikkei]] |date=1 March 2010 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> In June 2011, Spotify secured $100 million of funding and planned to use this to support its US launch. The new round of funding valued the company at $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify valued at $1bn, coming to US |url=http://www.investoo.co.uk/spotify-valued-at-1bn-coming-to-us/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325031236/http://www.investoo.co.uk/spotify-valued-at-1bn-coming-to-us/ |website=Investoo |date=18 June 2011 |archive-date=25 March 2012 |access-date=7 November 2016}}</ref> A [[Goldman Sachs]]-led round of funding closed in November 2012, raising around $100 million at a $3 billion valuation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Report: Spotify Has Closed A Massive Fifth Round Of Funding That Values It At $3 Billion |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/11/14/spotify-3-billion-round/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=14 November 2012 |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref>

In April 2015, Spotify began another round of fundraising, with a report from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' stating it was seeking $400 million, which would value the company at $8.4 billion.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Douglas |last1=MacMillan |first2=Telis |last2=Demos |title=Spotify Nears Deal to Raise $400 Million at $8.4 Billion Valuation |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-nears-deal-to-raise-400-million-at-8-4-billion-valuation-1428700668 |website=The Wall Street Journal |date=10 April 2015 |access-date=9 November 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The financing was closed in June 2015, with Spotify raising $526 million, at a value of $8.53 billion.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Douglas |last1=MacMillan |first2=Juhana |last2=Rossi |title=Spotify Raises $526 Million Amid Battle With Apple |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-scores-investment-from-teliasonera-in-multimillion-dollar-funding-round-1433918944 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=10 June 2015 |access-date=9 November 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In January 2016, Spotify raised another $500 million through convertible bonds.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Spotify Is Raising Another $500M In Convertible Notes With Discounts On IPO Shares |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/27/spotify-500-million/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=27 January 2016 |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref>

In March 2016, Spotify raised $1 billion in financing by debt plus a discount of 20% on shares once the [[initial public offering]] (IPO) of shares takes place.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Douglas |last1=MacMillan |first2=Matt |last2=Jarzemsky |first3=Maureen |last3=Farrell |title=Spotify Raises $1 Billion in Debt Financing |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-raises-1-billion-in-debt-financing-1459284467 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=29 March 2016 |access-date=9 November 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The company was, according to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', planning to launch on the [[stock market]] in 2017, but in 2017 it was seen as planning on doing the IPO in 2018 in order to "build up a better balance sheet and work on shifting its business model to improve its margins".<ref name="tc-ipo">{{cite web |first1=Ingrid |last1=Lunden |first2=Katie |last2=Roof |title=Sources: Spotify may delay IPO to 2018 as it rethinks licensing deals |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/02/02/sources-spotify-may-delay-ipo-to-2018-as-it-rethinks-licensing-deals/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=2 February 2017 |access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref>

=== Downloads ===
In March 2009, Spotify began offering [[music download]]s in the United Kingdom, France, and Spain. Users could purchase tracks from Spotify, which partnered with [[7digital]] to incorporate the feature. The ability to purchase and download music tracks via the app was removed on 4 January 2013.<ref name="No purchase" />

=== Spotify for Artists ===
In November 2015, Spotify introduced a "Fan Insights" panel in limited [[Software release life cycle|beta]] form, letting artists and managers access data on monthly listeners, geographical data, demographic information, music preferences and more.<ref>{{cite web |first=Romain |last=Dillett |title=Spotify Bets On Data To Lure Artists To Its Platform |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/17/spotify-bets-on-data-to-lure-artists-to-its-platform/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=17 November 2015 |access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, the panel was upgraded to leave beta status, renamed as "Spotify for Artists", and opened to all artists and managers. Additional features include the ability to get "verified" status with a blue checkmark on an artist's profile, receiving artist support from Spotify, customising the profile page with photos and promoting a certain song as their "pick".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Spotify's artist dashboard exits beta, offering streaming insights, profile management & more |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/18/spotifys-artist-dashboard-exits-beta-offering-streaming-insights-profile-management-more/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |date=18 April 2017 |access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Dan |last=Rys |title=Spotify Upgrades Fan Insights Feature to 'Spotify for Artists': Exclusive |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7761970/spotify-upgrades-fan-insights-spotify-for-artists-exclusive |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=18 April 2017 |access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref>

In September 2018, Spotify announced "Upload Beta", allowing artists to upload directly to the platform instead of going through a [[music industry|distributor]] or [[record label]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/20/17879840/spotify-artist-direct-upload-independent-music|title=Spotify will now let artists directly upload their music to the platform|last=Deahl|first=Dani|date=20 September 2018|website=The Verge|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> The feature was rolled out to a small number of US-based artists by invitation only. Uploading was free and artists received 100% of the revenue from songs they uploaded; artists were able to control when their release went public. On 1 July 2019, Spotify deprecated the program and announced plans to stop accepting direct uploads by the end of that month and eventually remove all content uploaded in this manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/spotify-independent-artists-upload-music-streaming/|title=Spotify shuts down direct music uploading for independent artists|last=Darus|first=Alex|date=2 July 2019|website=Alternative Press|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>

=== Industry initiatives ===
In June 2017, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that Spotify would announce "Secret Genius", a new initiative aimed at highlighting songwriters and producers, and the effect those people have on the music industry and the artists' careers. The project, which would feature awards, "Songshops" songwriting workshops, curated playlists, and podcasts, is an effort to "shine a light on these people behind the scenes who play such a big role in some of the most important moments of our lives. When the general public hears a song, they automatically associate it with the artist who sings it, not the people behind the scenes who make it happen, so we thought the title Secret Genius was appropriate", Spotify's former Global Head of Creator Services [[Troy Carter (talent manager)|Troy Carter]] told ''Variety'' the first awards ceremony would take place in late 2017,{{update inline|date=March 2019}} and was intended to honour "the top songwriters, producers and publishers in the industry as well as up-and-coming talent." Additionally, as part of "The Ambassador Program", 13 songwriters would each host a Songshop workshop, in which their peers would collaboratively attempt to create a hit song, with the first workshop taking place in Los Angeles in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jem |last=Aswad |title=Spotify Launches 'Secret Genius' Program to Celebrate Songwriters (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/exclusive-spotify-launches-secret-genius-for-songwriters-1202458229/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=8 June 2017 |access-date=9 June 2017}}</ref>

In October 2017, Spotify launched "Rise", a program aimed at promoting emerging artists.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Spotify launches RISE, a new emerging artist program |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/20/spotify-launches-a-rise-a-new-emerging-artist-program/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=20 October 2017 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Swapna |last=Krishna |title=Spotify's RISE program will try to find future music superstars |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/20/spotify-rise-emerging-artists/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=Oath Inc. |date=20 October 2017 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref> In February 2020, Spotify announced it would be featuring new songwriter pages and 'written by' playlists. This was aimed at giving fans a behind the scenes look at the process of some of their favorite songwriters. Initial pages added included Justin Trantor, [[Meghan Trainor]], and [[Missy Elliott]]. Spotify thereafter announced it was planning to add more of these pages and playlists to highlight songwriters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify rolls out Written By playlists as it expands support for songwriters and publishers|url=https://www.musicweek.com/digital/read/spotify-rolls-out-written-by-playlists-as-it-expands-support-for-songwriters-and-publishers/080354|access-date=21 July 2020|website=www.musicweek.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|date=9 July 2020|title=Spotify Adds Hundreds More Songwriter Pages and 'Written By' Playlists|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/9415812/spotify-adds-songwriter-pages-written-by-playlists|access-date=21 July 2020|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

In January 2021, Spotify made a selection of audiobooks available on the platform as a test of developing a greater breadth of content for users.<ref>{{cite web|date=25 January 2021|title=Spotify Tests Audiobooks With Classics Collection (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spotify-tests-audiobooks-with-frankenstein-jane-eyre-and-other-literary-classics-exclusive|access-date=25 January 2021|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en}}</ref> The addition of audiobooks to the service would create similar offerings to that of Amazon's [[Audible (service)|Audible]]. In 2020, Spotify partnered with [[Wizarding World]] to release a series of recorded readings of ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone,'' by various stars of the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carman|first=Ashley|date=5 May 2020|title=Daniel Radcliffe and others are reading chapters of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone on video|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/5/21247804/harry-potter-daniel-radcliffe-reading-philosophers-stone-spotify-video|access-date=25 January 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref>

=== Stations by Spotify ===
On 31 January 2018, Spotify started testing a new [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]]-styled standalone app called Stations by Spotify for Australian Android users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alphr.com/spotify/1008362/spotify-stations-app-playlists|title=Spotify's new Stations app is all about playlists without any of the faff|work=Alphr|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref> It featured 62 music channels, each devoted to a particular genre. Spotify itself has two channels named after its playlists that link directly to the users' profile: "Release Radar" and "Discover Weekly". The aim was to help users to listen to the music they want without [[information overload]] or spending time building their own playlists. At launch, the skipping feature was not featured to "reinforce the feel of radio", but it was quietly added later and with no limits. Songs can be "loved" but cannot be "hated". If a song is "loved", a custom radio channel will be created based on it, and when there are at least 15 of these songs, a "My Favourites" channel is unlocked.

The standalone app was made available to all iOS and Android users in the United States since 4 June 2019.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/4/18651865/spotify-stations-ios-release-date-news-features-australia-playlists Spotify Stations is now available in the US] – ''[[The Verge]]'' (published 4 June 2019)</ref>

Spotify announced the app would be shut down on 16 May 2022. The company said users would be able to login into the main Spotify app with their Stations account and transfer their stations into Spotify.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lawler |first1=Richard |title=Spotify will shut down its radio-like listening app Stations on May 16th |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/5/6/23060239/spotify-stations-experiment-may-16th-radio-pandora |website=The Verge |date=6 May 2022 |access-date=7 May 2022}}</ref>

