Spotify has client software currently available for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Wear OS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[watchOS]], [[iPadOS]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation 5]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Xbox Series X and Series S|Xbox Series X/S]] game consoles. There is an official, although unsupported Linux version. Spotify also offers a proprietary protocol known as "Spotify Connect", which lets users listen to music through a wide range of entertainment systems, including speakers, receivers, TVs, cars, and smartwatches. Spotify also has a web player (open.spotify.com).<ref name="Web player" /> Offline Music listening is possible on watchOS<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify on Apple Watch |url=https://support.spotify.com/us/article/spotify-on-apple-watch/ |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=Spotify |language=en-US}}</ref> and more recently added to google's WearOS<ref>{{Cite web |author1=Chris Wedel |date=2021-09-02 |title=How to use Spotify offline on Wear OS 3 watches |url=https://www.androidcentral.com/how-use-spotify-offline-wear-os-3-watches |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=Android Central |language=en}}</ref> for those with premium subscriptions. Unlike the apps, the web player does not have the ability to download music for offline listening. In June 2017, Spotify became available as an app through [[Windows Store]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Spotify is now available in the Windows Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/20/15840992/spotify-windows-store-app-download |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=20 June 2017 |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Andy |last=Weir |title=Spotify for Windows 10 PCs appears in the Windows Store, but you can't have it... [Update: Oh yes, you can!] |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/spotify-for-windows-10-pcs-appears-in-the-windows-store-but-you-can039t-have-it-yet |website=[[Neowin]] |date=20 June 2017 |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref>
[[File:Spotify on Desktop Arch Linux.png|alt=Playlist queue.|left|thumb|Spotify Desktop Client running on Arch Linux]]

=== Features ===
In Spotify's apps, music can be browsed or searched for via various parameters, such as artist, album, genre, [[playlist]], or record label. Users can create, edit and share playlists, share tracks on [[social media]], and make playlists with other users. Spotify provides access to over 70 million songs, 2.2 million podcasts and 4 billion playlists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotify vs. Apple Music: Which service is the streaming king? |url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/music/apple-music-vs-spotify/ |website=[[Digital Trends]] |date=28 October 2016 |access-date=14 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Russell |title=Spotify reaches 50 million paying users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/02/spotify-50-million/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=2 March 2017 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Spotify company info2" />

In November 2011, Spotify introduced a Spotify Apps service that made it possible for third-party developers to design applications that could be hosted within the Spotify computer software. The applications provided features such as synchronised lyrics, music reviews, and song recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stuart |last=Dredge |title=Spotify amps up iTunes rivalry with its own apps platform |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/appsblog/2011/nov/30/spotify-apps-platform |website=The Guardian |date=30 November 2011 |access-date=8 November 2016}}</ref> In June 2012, Soundrop became the first Spotify app to attract major funding, receiving $3 million from Spotify investor Northzone.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Cheredar |title=Even Spotify apps are getting funded: Soundrop raises $3M to turn music social |url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/06/12/soundrop/ |website=[[VentureBeat]] |date=12 June 2012 |access-date=8 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Spotify App Soundrop Tunes Into First Investment: $3M From Spotify Lead Backer Northzone |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/06/11/spotify-app-soundrop-tunes-into-first-investment-3m-from-spotify-lead-backer-northzone/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=11 June 2012 |access-date=8 November 2016}}</ref> However, after the June 2014 announcement of a Web [[API]] that allowed third-party developers to integrate Spotify content in their own web applications, the company discontinued its Spotify Apps platform in October, stating that its new development tools for the Spotify web player fulfilled many of the advantages of the former Spotify Apps service, but "would ensure the Spotify platform remained relevant and easy to develop on, as well as enabling you to build innovative and engaging music experiences".<ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Spotify Axes App Finder, Kills Soundrop And Its Listening Rooms |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/13/rip-spotify-apps-rip-soundrop/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |date=13 November 2014 |access-date=8 November 2016}}</ref>

In April 2012, Spotify introduced a "Spotify Play Button", an embeddable music player that can be added to blogs, websites, or social media profiles, that lets visitors listen to a specific song, playlist, or album without leaving the page.<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Spotify's New Embeddable Play Button Lets Any Site Turn You On To Legal Tunes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/11/spotify-play-button/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=11 April 2012 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> The following November, the company began rolling out a web player, with a similar design to its computer programs, but without the requirement of any installation.<ref name="Web player">{{cite web |first=Ellis |last=Hamburger |title=Spotify to begin rolling out browser-based music app in beta today |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/11/15/3649068/spotify-browser-player-web-app |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=15 November 2012 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref>

In December 2012, Spotify introduced a "Follow" tab and a "Discover" tab, along with a "Collection" section. "Follow" lets users follow artists and friends to see what they are listening to, while "Discover" directs users to new releases as well as music, review, and concert recommendations based on listening history. Users can add tracks to a "Collection" section of the app, rather than adding them to a specific playlist.<ref name="verge-collection">{{cite web |first=Ellis |last=Hamburger |title=Spotify debuts new Discovery engine, Collection, and Follow, which lets users follow friends and celebrities |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/12/6/3736018/spotify-debuts-new-discovery-engine-collection-and-follow-which-lets |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=6 December 2012 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Christina |last=Warren |title=Spotify Wants to Make Music Discovery Truly Social |url=http://mashable.com/2012/12/06/spotify-social-discovery/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=6 December 2012 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref> The features were announced by CEO Daniel Ek at a press conference, with Ek saying that a common user complaint about the service was that "Spotify is great when you know what music you want to listen to, but not when you don't".<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Nate |last=Lanxon |title=Spotify announces major updates to service, gets Metallica catalogue |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-12/06/spotify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209203636/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-12/06/spotify |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=6 December 2012 |archive-date=9 December 2012 |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref>

In May 2015, Spotify announced a new "Home" start-page that could recommend music. The company also introduced "Spotify Running", a feature aimed at improving music while running with music matched to running tempo, and announced that [[podcast]]s and videos ("entertainment, news and clips") would be coming to Spotify, along with "Spotify Originals" content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Welch |title=Spotify now does videos and podcasts |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/5/20/8629335/spotify-adds-podcasts-videos |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=20 May 2015 |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/new-features-packed-inside-spotify/|title=Here are all the new features packed inside Spotify|last=Moynihan|first=Tim|date=20 May 2017|journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Crook |title=Spotify Introduces Video Clips, Podcasts, And Activity-Based Playlists |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/20/spotify-introduces-video-clips-podcasts-and-activity-based-playlists/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |date=20 May 2015 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref>

In December 2015, Spotify debuted [[Spotify Wrapped]], a program that creates playlists based on each user's most listened-to songs from the year. Users then can view and save this playlist at the end of the year.   While it continued to provide users with an end-of-the-year wrap up, the playlist feature was later removed.<ref>{{cite web|date=7 December 2020|title=How Spotify Wrapped Has Evolved Over The Years|url=https://screenrant.com/spotify-wrapped-stats-features-evolution/|access-date=5 April 2021|website=ScreenRant|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Swant|first=Marty|title=Spotify Rolls Out New 'Wrapped' Campaign To Help Users Remember Their Decade Of Music|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/martyswant/2019/12/17/spotify-rolls-out-new-wrapped-campaign-help-users-remember-their-decade-of-music/|access-date=5 April 2021|website=Forbes|language=en}}</ref>

In January 2016, Spotify and music annotation service [[Genius (website)|Genius]] formed a partnership, bringing annotation information from Genius into infocards presented while songs are playing in Spotify. The functionality is limited to selected playlists and was only available on Spotify's iOS app at launch,<ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Spotify And Genius Team To Stream The Backstory On Music Tracks |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/12/spotify-teams-with-genius-to-annotate-music-tracks/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=12 January 2016 |access-date=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Noah |last=Kulwin |title=Spotify Adds 'Behind the Lyrics' Playlists, Powered by Lyrics Site Genius |url=https://www.recode.net/2016/1/12/11588702/spotify-adds-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-powered-by-lyrics-site-genius |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=12 January 2016 |access-date=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jamieson |last=Cox |title=Spotify and Genius are collaborating on info-rich Behind the Lyrics playlists |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/12/10750990/spotify-genius-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-iphone |website=[[The Verge]] |date=12 January 2016 |access-date=30 March 2017}}</ref> being expanded to the Android app in April 2017. This feature was known as "Behind the Lyrics".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Spotify brings "Behind the Lyrics" to Android |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/25/spotify-brings-its-behind-the-lyrics-annotations-to-android/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Dalton |title=Spotify took its sweet time getting Behind the Lyrics on Android |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/25/spotify-behind-the-lyrics-on-android/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref> As of November 18, 2021, "Behind the Lyrics" has been replaced with auto-generated real-time lyrics due to consumer demand. The feature is powered by lyrics provider Musixmatch.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2021/11/18/spotify-finally-rolls-out-real-time-lyrics-to-global-users/ Spotify finally rolls out real-time lyrics to global users] - ''TechCrunch (published November 18, 2021)</ref>

In May 2017, Spotify introduced Spotify Codes for its mobile apps, a way for users to share specific artists, tracks, playlists or albums with other people. Users find the relevant content to share and press a "soundwave-style barcode" on the display. A camera icon in the apps' search fields lets other users point their device's camera at the code, which takes them to the same content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Natt |last=Garun |title=Spotify adds QR-like codes for quick music sharing |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/5/15562198/spotify-scannable-codes-music-sharing-mobile |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=5 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Scan these new QR-style Spotify Codes to instantly play a song |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/05/spotify-codes/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=5 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan |last=Clark |title=Spotify Codes bring Snapchat-like QR codes to music streaming |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2017/05/05/spotify-codes-bring-snapchat-like-qr-codes-to-music-streaming/ |website=The Next Web |date=5 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref>

In January 2019, Spotify introduced Car View for Android, allowing devices running Android to have a compact Now Playing screen when the device is connected to a car's Bluetooth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xda-developers.com/spotify-safety-mode-ui-bluetooth/|title=[Update: Rolling out as 'Car View'] Spotify tests stripped-down "Safety Mode" UI when connected to Bluetooth devices|date=18 January 2019|website=xda-developers|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/16/18185644/spotify-car-view-now-testing-android-simple-controls|title=Spotify launches a simplified Car View for controlling your music while driving|last=Welch|first=Chris|date=16 January 2019|website=The Verge|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref> Also in January 2019, Spotify beta-tested its Canvas feature, where artists and/or labels can upload looping 3 to 8-second moving visuals to their tracks, replacing album covers in the "Now Playing" view; users have the option to turn off this feature. Canvas is only available for Spotify's iOS and Android mobile apps.<ref>[https://www.hypebot.com/hypebot/2019/01/with-spotify-canvas-artists-can-add-moving-visuals-to-tracks.html With Spotify Canvas, Artists Add Moving Visuals To Tracks] – Hyperbot.com (published 31 January 2019)</ref> Months later, Spotify tested its own version of stories (the sharing format popularized by social apps) known as "Storyline", and the focus is on allowing artists to share their own insights, inspiration, details about their creative process or other meanings behind the music.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/13/spotify-is-testing-its-own-version-of-stories-called-storyline/ Spotify is testing its own version of Stories called 'Storyline'] - ''TechCrunch'' (published May 13, 2019)</ref>

In March 2021, Spotify announced an upcoming option for higher-resolution sound, Spotify Hi-Fi.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Mark |title=Streaming for Audiophiles |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/streaming-for-audiophiles-11615243830?mod=tech_lista_pos2 |access-date=11 March 2021 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=8 March 2021}}</ref>

==== Playlists and discovery ====
In July 2015, Spotify launched Discover Weekly, a playlist generated weekly.  Updated on Mondays, it provides users with music recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kia |last=Kokalitcheva |title=Spotify's new feature will help you fight the Monday blues |url=http://fortune.com/2015/07/20/spotify-discovery-playlists/ |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |date=20 July 2015 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Stuart |last=Dredge |title=Spotify bites back at Apple Music with weekly 'mixtape' playlist for each user |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/20/spotify-apple-music-weekly-mixtape-playlist |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=20 July 2015 |access-date=6 June 2017}}</ref> In December 2015, ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' reported that songs in Discover Weekly playlists had been streamed 1.7 billion times,.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adam |last=Pasick |title=The magic that makes Spotify's Discover Weekly playlists so damn good |url=http://qz.com/571007/the-magic-that-makes-spotifys-discover-weekly-playlists-so-damn-good/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]  |date=21 December 2015 |access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref>

In March 2016, Spotify launched six playlists branded as Fresh Finds, including the main playlist and Fire Emoji, Basement, Hiptronix, Six Strings, and Cyclone (hip-hop, electronic, pop, guitar-driven, and experimental music respectively). The playlists spotlight songs by lesser-known musicians and their songs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-introduces-fresh-finds-playlists-2016-3|title=Spotify now has even more playlists to help you find hot new music|work=Business Insider|access-date=10 June 2018}}</ref>

In August 2016, Spotify launched Release Radar, a personalized playlist that allows users to stay up-to-date on new music released by the artists they listen to the most. It also helps users discover new music, by mixing in other artists' music. The playlist is updated every Friday, and is a maximum of two hours in length.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Popper |title=Spotify's Release Radar is a personalized playlist of brand-new music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/5/12380816/spotify-release-radar-personalized-discovery-curation |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=5 August 2016 |access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Spotify follows Discover Weekly with personalized new releases playlist |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/05/spotify-release-radar/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=5 August 2016 |access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref>

The RADAR program is Spotify's global artist program, exclusively designed to help emerging artists worldwide reach the next stage in their careers and strengthen their connection to listeners. {{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

Spotify provides artists taking part in RADAR with resources and access to integrated marketing opportunities to help them boost their careers, in addition to expanded reach and exposure to 178 markets worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|date=30 May 2021|title=The Tea with AleXa: An Exclusive Interview with the K-Pop Sensation!|url=https://www.el-shai.com/alexa-exclusive-interview-with-the-k-pop-sensation/|access-date=3 October 2021|website=El-Shai|language=en-US}}</ref>

In September 2016, Spotify introduced Daily Mix, a series of (up to six) playlists that mixes the user's favorite tracks with new, recommended songs. New users can access Daily Mix after approximately two weeks of listening to music through Spotify. Daily Mixes were only available on the Android and iOS mobile apps at launch, but the feature was later expanded to Spotify's computer app in December 2016.{{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

In 2017, Spotify introduced RapCaviar, a hip-hop playlist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/apple-music-takes-on-spotifys-influential-rapcaviar-with-rap-life-playlist-and-weekly-show/|title=Apple Music takes on Spotify's influential RapCaviar brand with Rap Life playlist and weekly show|date=19 July 2019|website=Music Business Worldwide}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/spotify-rapcaviar-most-influential-playlist-in-music.html |title=How a Hit Happens Now |first=Craig |last=Marks |work=Vulture |date=September 2017 |access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> Rap Caviar had 10.9 million followers by 2019, becoming one of Spotify's Top 5 playlists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://routenote.com/blog/rap-caviar-spotify/|title=What is Rap Caviar on Spotify?|date=9 February 2018}}</ref> RapCaviar was originally curated by Tuma Basa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/meet-tuma-basa-the-mastermind-behind-spotify-s-rap-caviar-playlist|title=Meet Tuma Basa, The Mastermind Behind Spotify's 'Rap Caviar' Playlist|website=Genius}}</ref> It was  relaunched by Carl Chery in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketingdive.com/news/spotify-sculpts-cardi-b-other-hip-hop-stars-for-latest-rapcaviar-pantheon/551795/|title=Spotify sculpts Cardi B, other hip-hop stars for latest RapCaviar pantheon|website=Marketing Dive}}</ref>

In July 2018, Spotify introduced a beta feature that gives artists, labels, and teams an easy way to submit unreleased music directly to Spotify's editorial team for playlist consideration. {{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

In June 2019, Spotify launched a custom playlist titled "Your Daily Drive" that closely replicates the [[drive time]] format of many traditional radio stations. It combines short-form podcast news updates from [[The Wall Street Journal]], [[NPR]], and [[Public Radio International|PRI]] with a mix of a user's favorite songs and artists interspersed with tracks the listener has yet to discover. "Your Daily Drive", which is found in a user's library under the "Made For You" section, updates throughout the day.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/177736/spotify-launches-your-daily-drive-with-custom-music-and-news-updates/ Spotify Launches Your Daily Drive With Custom Music And News Updates] – ''Radio Insight'' (published 12 June 2019; accessed 13 June 2019)</ref>

In May 2020, Spotify introduced the Group Session feature. This feature allows two or more Premium users in the same location to share control over the music that's being played.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clover |first1=Juli |title=Spotify Gains New 'Group Session' Feature With Shared Listening Queue |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/05/11/spotify-adds-group-session-feature/ |website=Mac Rumors |access-date=12 May 2020}}</ref> The Group Session feature was later expanded to allow any Premium user to join/participate in a Group Session, with a special link the host can send to participants.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 July 2020|title=Your Squad Can Now Stream Simultaneously Using Spotify's Group Session Beta|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2020-07-28/your-squad-can-now-stream-simultaneously-using-spotifys-group-session-beta/|access-date=10 May 2021|website=Spotify Newsroom|language=en-US}}</ref>

In July 2021, Spotify launched the "What's New" feed, a section that collects all new releases and episodes from artists and podcasts that the user follows. The feature is represented by a bell icon on the app's main page and is available on iOS and Android.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 July 2021 |title=Spotify adds What's New feed for all the music and podcasts you follow |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/27/22595581/spotify-whats-new-feed-podcasts-artists-follow |access-date=27 July 2021|website=The Verge |language=en-US}}</ref>

In November 2021, Spotify launched the City and Local Pulse charts, aimed at representing the songs listened to in major cities around the world. The charts are available for 200 cities with the most listeners on Spotify.<ref>{{cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |title= Spotify Expands Charts to Include Genre and Local Categories |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-charts-genre-local-1235108909/ |date=10 November 2021 |access-date=12 November 2021 |website=Variety |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Listening limitations ===
Spotify has experimented with different limitations to users' listening on the Free service tier.

In April 2011, Spotify announced via a blog post that they would drastically cut the amount of music that free members could access, effective 1 May 2011. The post stated that all free members would be limited to ten hours of music streaming per month, and in addition, individual tracks were limited to five plays. New users were exempt from these changes for six months.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Butcher |title=Spotify takes the axe to its free service – can it now claim to slash music piracy? |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/04/14/spotify-takes-the-axe-to-its-free-service-can-it-now-claim-to-slash-music-piracy/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=14 April 2011 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref> In March 2013, the five-play individual track limit was removed for users in the United Kingdom, and media reports stated that users in the United States, Australia, and New Zealand never had the limit in the first place.<ref>{{cite web |first=Steve |last=O'Hear |title=Spotify Ditches Its 5 Play Limit For Spotify Free Users In The UK |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/19/spotify-freetards/ |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |date=19 March 2013 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Shane |last=Richmond |title=Spotify removes five-play song cap |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/9940432/Spotify-removes-five-play-song-cap.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/9940432/Spotify-removes-five-play-song-cap.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=19 March 2013 |access-date=2 June 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In December 2013, CEO Daniel Ek announced that Android and iOS smartphone users with the free service tier could listen to music in Shuffle mode, a feature in which users can stream music by specific artists and playlists without being able to pick which songs to hear. Mobile listening previously was not allowed in Spotify Free accounts. Ek stated that "We're giving people the best free music experience in the history of the smartphone."<ref>{{cite news |first=Ellis |last=Hamburger |title=Spotify announces free streaming on Android and iPhone, but only in Shuffle mode |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/12/11/5199692/spotify-announces-free-streaming-on-android-and-iphone-but-only-in |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=11 December 2013 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Crook |title=Spotify Goes Freemium On Tablets, Launches Free Shuffle Product On Smartphones |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/11/spotify-launches-spotify-free-for-tablets/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date= 11 December 2013 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref> This shuffle feature is not available on Android and iOS tablets, or computers.

In January 2014, Spotify removed all time limits for Free users on all platforms, including on computers, which previously had a 10-hour monthly listening limit after a 6-month grace period.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sophie |last=Murray-Morris |title=Spotify removes time restrictions on free desktop player |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/spotify-removes-time-restrictions-for-desktop-listening-9062361.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220524/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/spotify-removes-time-restrictions-for-desktop-listening-9062361.html |archive-date=24 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |website=[[The Independent]] |date=15 January 2014 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Constine |title=Spotify Drops Free Web Listening Time Limit Everywhere – A Big Scalability Milestone |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/01/15/spotify-limits/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |date=15 January 2014 |access-date=2 June 2017}}</ref>

In April 2018, Spotify began to allow Free users to listen on-demand to whatever songs they want for an unlimited number of times, as long as the song is on one of the user's 15 personalized discovery playlists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/24/spotify-beefs-up-its-free-tier-as-apple-music-gains-traction/|title=Spotify beefs up its free tier – TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|date=24 April 2018 |access-date=24 April 2018}}</ref>

Before April 2020, all service users were limited to 10,000 songs in their library, after which they would receive an "Epic collection, friend" notification and would not be able to save more music to their library. Adding playlists at this point also arbitrarily removed older playlists from the users' library. Spotify later removed this limit.

