Spotify is [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] and uses [[digital rights management]] (DRM) controls.<ref name="DRM" /> Spotify's [[terms and conditions]] do not permit users to [[Reverse engineering|reverse-engineer]] the application.

Spotify allows users to add local audio files for music not in its catalog into the user's library through Spotify's desktop application, and then allows users to synchronize those music files to Spotify's mobile apps or other computers over the same [[Wi-Fi]] network as the primary computer by creating a Spotify playlist, and adding those local audio files to the playlist. Audio files must either be in the .mp3, .mp4 (.mp4 files that have video streams are not supported), or .m4p media formats. This feature is available only for Premium subscribers.

Spotify has a median playback latency of 265 ms (including local [[cache (computing)|cache]]).<ref>{{cite web |first1=Gunnar |last1=Kreitz |first2=Fredrik |last2=Niemelä |title=Spotify – Large Scale, Low Latency, P2P Music-on-Demand Streaming |url=http://www.csc.kth.se/~gkreitz/spotify-p2p10/spotify-p2p10.pdf |publisher=[[Royal Institute of Technology]] |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref>

In April 2014, Spotify moved away from the [[peer-to-peer]] (P2P) system they had used to distribute music to users. Previously, a desktop user would listen to music from one of three sources: a cached file on the computer, one of Spotify's servers, or from other subscribers through the P2P system. P2P, a well-established Internet distribution system, served as an alternative that reduced Spotify's server resources and costs. However, Spotify ended the P2P setup in 2014, with Spotify's Alison Bonny telling [[TorrentFreak]]: "We're gradually phasing out the use of our desktop P2P technology which has helped our users enjoy their music both speedily and seamlessly. We're now at a stage where we can power music delivery through our growing number of servers and ensure our users continue to receive a best-in-class service."<ref>{{cite web |author=Ernesto |title=Spotify Starts Shutting Down Its Massive P2P Network |url=https://torrentfreak.com/spotify-starts-shutting-down-its-massive-p2p-network-140416/ |publisher=[[TorrentFreak]] |date=16 April 2014 |access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref>

Originally Spotify had their own servers but in 2016 most of their infrastructure was migrated to [[Google Cloud Platform|Google cloud]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Toor |first=Amar |date=2016-02-24 |title=Spotify is moving its data to Google's servers |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/2/24/11104446/spotify-google-cloud-platform |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref>

=== Car Thing ===
Spotify first announced a voice-activated music-streaming gadget for cars in May 2019. Named the Car Thing, it represents the music-streaming service's first entry into hardware devices.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sapra|first=Bani|title=We just got our best look yet at Spotify's mysterious music streaming gadget, the Car Thing, and it has built-in LTE wireless|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-car-thing-photos-details-user-manual-2020-1|access-date=8 April 2021|website=Business Insider}}</ref> In early 2020, as part of filings to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), submitted images of the device that make it seem much more like a miniature infotainment screen.<ref>{{cite web|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2 April 2021|title=Spotify leaks another look at the Car Thing, this time from within in its own app|url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/4/2/22364630/spotify-car-thing-renders-app-leak-music-player-hardware-product|access-date=8 April 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref> In April 2021, Spotify rolled out its own voice assistant with the hands-free wake word: "Hey Spotify".<ref>{{cite web|title=Hands-free "Hey Spotify" wake word rolls out|url=https://www.gsmarena.com/handsfree_hey_spotify_wake_word_rolls_out-news-48521.php|access-date=8 April 2021|website=GSMArena.com|language=en-US}}</ref> Using this, users can perform various actions such as pulling playlists, launching radio stations, playing or pausing songs. This voice-based virtual assistant may be intended more towards Spotify's own hardware such as its "Car Thing".<ref>{{cite web|last=Hollister|first=Sean|date=7 April 2021|title="Hey Spotify" is another hands-free way to control your music, rolling out now|url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/4/7/22371866/hey-spotify-voice-assistant-hands-free-android-ios-iphone|access-date=8 April 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref>

== Geographic availability ==
<ref>{{cite web|date=22 February 2021|title=Spotify Expands International Footprint, Bringing Audio to 80+ New Markets|url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2021-02-22/spotify-expands-international-footprint-bringing-audio-to-80-new-markets/|access-date=24 February 2021|website=Spotify|language=en-US}}</ref> The company is incorporated in Luxembourg as '''Spotify Technology S.A.''',<ref>{{cite web|title=EDGAR Filing Documents for 0001639920-21-000006|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1639920/000163992021000006/0001639920-21-000006-index.htm|access-date=14 April 2021|website=www.sec.gov}}</ref> and is headquartered in [[Stockholm]], Sweden, with offices in 16 countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spotify Technology S.a.|url=https://lei.report/LEI/549300B4X0JHWV0DTD60|access-date=10 March 2021|website=lei.report}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Listening is everything|url=https://www.spotify.com/us/about-us/contact/|access-date=10 March 2021|website=www.spotify.com|language=en}}</ref> Following the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine]], Spotify temporarily closed its office in Russia<ref>{{cite news |title=Spotify closes its office in Russia in response to attack on Ukraine until further notice.|url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/spotify-closes-its-office-russia-response-attack-ukraine-2022-03-02/ |access-date=25 March 2022 |work=Reuters |date=3 March 2022}}</ref> and suspended both premium and free services from the country until further notice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Lucas |title=Spotify Pulls Free Service From Russia, Completing Its Exit |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-03-25/spotify-pulls-free-service-from-russia-completing-its-exit |access-date=25 March 2022 |work=Bloomberg |date=25 March 2022}}</ref> However, the support service continues to work for Russian users.{{citation needed|date=April 2022}}

