== Criticism ==
{{Main|Criticism of Spotify}}
Spotify has attracted significant criticism since its 2006 launch.<ref name="Launch">{{cite web|title=We've only just begun!|url=https://news.spotify.com/us/2008/10/07/weve-only-just-begun/|date=7 October 2008|publisher=Spotify|access-date=7 November 2016|archive-date=11 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211213512/https://news.spotify.com/us/2008/10/07/weve-only-just-begun/|url-status=dead}}</ref> The primary point of criticism centres around what artists, music creators, and the media have described as "unsustainable" compensation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lizzie |last=Plaugic |title=Spotify's Year in Music shows just how little we pay artists for their music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/7/9861372/spotify-year-in-review-artist-payment-royalties |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=7 December 2015 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> Unlike physical sales or legal downloads (both of which were the main medium of listening to music at the time), which pay artists a fixed amount per song or album sold, Spotify pays royalties based on their "market share": the number of streams for their songs as a proportion of total songs streamed on the service. Spotify distributes approximately 70% of its total revenue to rights-holders, who will then pay artists based on their individual agreements.<ref name="Spotify business" /> Worldwide, 30,000 musicians have joined the organization UnionOfMusicians (UMAW).<ref name="auto2">{{cite web|title=Has Streaming Saved the Music Industry? - Tracks – Watch the full show|url=https://www.arte.tv/en/videos/100280-007-A/has-streaming-saved-the-music-industry/|url-status=dead|access-date=28 October 2021|website=ARTE|language=en|archive-date=29 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211129150425/https://www.arte.tv/en/videos/100280-007-A/has-streaming-saved-the-music-industry/}}</ref> UMAW organized protests in 31 cities in March 2021 and its campaign #JusticeAtSpotify is demanding more transparency and a compensation of one cent per stream.<ref name="auto2" />

Spotify has been criticised by artists and producers including [[Thom Yorke]] and [[Taylor Swift]], who have argued that Spotify does not fairly compensate musicians, and both withdrew their music from the service.<ref>{{cite web |title=Thom Yorke pulls albums from Spotify |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23313445 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 July 2013 |access-date=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Charlotte |last=Alter |title=Taylor Swift Just Removed Her Music From Spotify |url=http://time.com/3554438/taylor-swift-spotify/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=3 November 2014 |access-date=23 December 2016}}</ref> Their catalogues returned to the service in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=Derrick |last=Rossignol |title=Thom Yorke's Solo Albums Are Finally Streaming On Spotify, Which He Famously Hates |url=http://uproxx.com/music/thom-yorke-spotify-streaming/ |website=[[Uproxx]] |publisher=[[Uproxx Media Group]] |date=8 December 2017 |access-date=10 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Taylor Swift's Music Returning to Spotify & Other Streaming Services Tonight |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7825570/taylor-swift-spotify-streaming-again |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=8 June 2017 |access-date=9 June 2017}}</ref> While the streaming music industry in general faces the same critique about inadequate payments,<ref>{{cite web |title=What Streaming Music Services Pay |url=http://www.informationisbeautiful.net/visualizations/spotify-apple-music-tidal-music-streaming-services-royalty-rates-compared/ |website=[[David McCandless|Information is Beautiful]] |access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref> Spotify, being the leading service,<ref>{{cite web |first=Micah |last=Singleton |title=Spotify now has 140 million active users |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/15/15807826/spotify-140-million-active-users |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=15 June 2017 |access-date=10 December 2017}}</ref> faces particular scrutiny due to its free service tier, allowing users to listen to music for free, though with advertisements between tracks. The free service tier has led to a variety of major album releases being delayed or withdrawn from the service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Hannah |last=Karp |title=Coldplay to Headline Super Bowl Halftime Show |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coldplay-to-headline-super-bowl-halftime-show-1449174658 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=3 December 2015 |access-date=24 December 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |first=Victor |last=Luckerson |title=Beyoncé's Latest Album Is Finally on Spotify |url=http://time.com/3602610/beyonce-spotify/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=24 November 2014 |access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Austin |last=Carr |title=Why Spotify Turned Down Adele's ''21'' |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1816582/why-spotify-turned-down-adeles-21 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=15 February 2012 |access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> In response to the allegations about unfair compensation, Spotify claims that it is benefitting the industry by migrating users away from [[Copyright infringement|unauthorized copying]] and less monetized platforms to its free service tier, and then downgrades that service until they upgrade to paid accounts.<ref name="Spotify business" /> A study has shown that [[record label]]s keep a high amount of the money earned from Spotify,<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Ingham |title=Major labels keep 73% of Spotify Premium payouts – Report |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/artists-get-7-of-streaming-cash-labels-take-46/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |date=3 February 2015 |access-date=17 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Masnick |title=Yes, Major Record Labels Are Keeping Nearly All The Money They Get From Spotify, Rather Than Giving It To Artists |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20150204/07310329906/yes-major-record-labels-are-keeping-nearly-all-money-they-get-spotify-rather-than-giving-it-to-artists.shtml |publisher=Techdirt |date=5 February 2015 |access-date=17 December 2016}}</ref> and the CEO of [[Merlin Network]], a representative body for over 10,000 independent labels, has also observed significant yearly growth rates in earnings from Spotify, while clarifying that Spotify pays labels, not artists.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eliot Van |last=Buskirk |title=David Lowery Might Be Right About Some Things, But He's Wrong About Streaming, Money, and Artists |url=http://evolver.fm/2012/06/21/david-lowery-might-be-right-about-some-things-but-hes-wrong-about-streaming-money-and-artists/ |publisher=Evolver.fm |date=21 June 2012 |access-date=17 December 2016 |archive-date=2 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202073932/http://evolver.fm/2012/06/21/david-lowery-might-be-right-about-some-things-but-hes-wrong-about-streaming-money-and-artists/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2017, as part of its efforts to renegotiate licence deals for an interest in [[Initial public offering|going public]], Spotify announced that artists would be able to make albums temporarily exclusive to paid subscribers if the albums are part of [[Universal Music Group]] or the Merlin Network.

In May 2018, Spotify attracted criticism for its "Hate Content & Hateful Conduct policy" that removed the music of [[R. Kelly]] and [[XXXTentacion]] from its editorial and algorithmic playlists because "When we look at promotion, we look at issues around hateful conduct, where you have an artist or another creator who has done something off-platform that is so particularly out of line with our values, egregious, in a way that it becomes something that we don't want to associate ourselves with." R. Kelly has faced accusations of sexual abuse, while XXXTentacion was on trial for domestic abuse in a case that did not reach a judgement before [[killing of XXXTentacion|his death]] that June.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Strauss |first1=Matthew |title=Spotify Removes R. Kelly and XXXTentacion From Its Playlists |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/spotify-removes-r-kelly-from-its-playlists/ |access-date=21 October 2018 |work=Pitchfork |date=10 May 2018}}</ref> This policy was revoked in June because the company deemed the original wording to be too "vague"; they stated that "Across all genres, our role is not to regulate artists. Therefore, we are moving away from implementing a policy around artist conduct".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minsker |first1=Evan |last2=Yoo |first2=Noah |title=Spotify Walks Back Controversial "Hateful Conduct" Policy, Adds XXXTentacion to Major Playlist |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/spotify-walks-back-controversial-hateful-conduct-policy/ |access-date=21 October 2018 |work=Pitchfork |date=1 June 2018}}</ref> However, artists such as [[Gary Glitter]] and [[Lostprophets]] are still hidden from Spotify's radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/spotify-hateful-conduct-axl-rose-r-kelly-jimmy-page-and-eminem-w890kwc3l|title=Where will Spotify's censorship end?|first=Dan Cairns and Jonathan|last=Dean|date=27 May 2018|work=The Times}}</ref>

According to some computer science and music experts, various music communities are often ignored or overlooked by music streaming services, such as Spotify.<ref name="Rolling Stone 2019">{{cite magazine | title=Spotify Pivots on Global Cultures Initiative, Alarming Music Industry | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=4 October 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/spotify-global-cultures-initiative-892762/ | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name="Hepworth 2020">{{cite web | last=Hepworth | first=Shelley | title=Streaming spells the end of the 'ownership' era of music, but are we ready to let go? | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=1 January 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/02/streaming-spells-the-end-of-the-ownership-era-of-music-but-are-we-ready-to-let-go | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name="Lucero 2020">{{cite web | last=Lucero | first=Mario J. | title=The problem with how the music streaming industry handles data | website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] | date=3 January 2020 | url=https://qz.com/1773480/the-problem-with-how-the-music-streaming-industry-handles-data/ | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name="RouteNote Blog 2020">{{cite web | title=Spotify and streaming services are breaking cultural music on a worldwide stage | website=RouteNote Blog | date=6 February 2020 | url=http://routenote.com/blog/spotify-and-streaming-services-are-breaking-cultural-music-on-a-worldwide-stage/ | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> The most commonly perceived error is said to be caused by a lack of diverse scope within curation staff, including overlooking mainstay artists in large genres, potentially causing a categorical homogenization of musical styles; even impacting mainline artists like within [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] with [[A Tribe Called Quest]].<ref name="Hepworth 2020" /> This can potentially have a negative impact on heritage styles, amongst both popular and traditional genres of [[New Mexico music]] and [[folk music]], and possibly hindering the growth of styles such as [[country rap]] and [[contemporary Christian music]].<ref name="Lucero 2020" />

In 2016, Spotify was criticized for allegedly making certain artists' music harder to find than others as these artists would release their music to the rival streaming service [[Apple Music]] before releasing it to Spotify.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 August 2016|title=Spotify Is Burying Musicians for Their Apple Deals|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-26/spotify-said-to-retaliate-against-artists-with-apple-exclusives|access-date=22 July 2020|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref>

In March 2021, David Dayen argued in ''The American Prospect'' <ref name="prospect.org">{{cite web|url=https://prospect.org/api/content/b969aae6-89e3-11eb-a885-1244d5f7c7c6/|title=Islands in the Stream|first=David|last=Dayen|date=22 March 2021|website=The American Prospect}}</ref> that musicians were in peril due to monopolies in streaming services like Spotify. Daniel Ek, co-founder and CEO of Spotify, discussed "what he called an artist-friendly streaming solution." He explained, "An extension of the internet radio craze of the early 2000s, Spotify would license content from record labels, and then support artists as people listened to their music."<ref name="prospect.org" /> However, Dayen noted that such services draw revenue from advertisements, the promise of audience growth to investors, and data collection.{{Citation needed|date=January 2022}}

=== ''The Joe Rogan Experience'' ===
{{Main|The Joe Rogan Experience}}
[[File: Joerogan.jpg|thumb|[[Joe Rogan]], host of ''The Joe Rogan Experience'']]
In 2020, Spotify received criticism from anti-misinformation groups when conspiracy theorist [[Alex Jones]] appeared on [[Joe Rogan]]'s podcast, ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|date=29 October 2020|title=Spotify and Joe Rogan under fire over Alex Jones role|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-54733252|access-date=29 October 2020}}</ref> Spotify's employees raised concerns about Jones' appearance on the show.<ref>{{Cite news|date=28 October 2020|title=Spotify's Own Employees Fret About Alex Jones Appearing on Joe Rogan Show|language=en|work=Bloomberg.com|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-10-28/spotify-draws-fire-over-alex-jones-s-claims-in-joe-rogan-podcast|access-date=29 October 2020}}</ref> In 2021, Spotify removed 42 episodes of Rogan's podcast.<ref>{{cite web|date=7 April 2021|title=Spotify Continues to Remove Joe Rogan Episodes — 42 Shows Deleted|url=https://www.digitalmusicnews.com/2021/04/06/joe-rogan-spotify-removing-shows/|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Digital Music News|language=en-US}}</ref>

In January 2022, 270 scientists, physicians, professors, doctors, healthcare workers, veterinarians, a dentist, psychologists, physicians' assistants, medical students, an engineer and a podcast host wrote an open letter to Spotify expressing concern over "false and societally harmful assertions" on ''The Joe Rogan Experience'' and asked Spotify to "establish a clear and public policy to moderate misinformation on its platform". The 270 signatories objected to Rogan broadcasting [[COVID-19 misinformation]], citing "a highly controversial" episode featuring guest [[Robert W. Malone|Robert Malone]] (#1757). The episode has been criticized for "promoting baseless conspiracy theories", including "an unfounded theory that societal leaders have 'hypnotized' the public." The signatories assert: "Dr. Malone is one of two recent JRE guests who has compared pandemic policies to [[the Holocaust]]. These actions are not only objectionable and offensive, but also medically and culturally dangerous." The signatories also note that Malone was [[Twitter suspensions|suspended from Twitter]] for spreading misinformation about COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tapp|first=Tom|date=13 January 2022|title=Hundreds Of Doctors Sign Open Letter Asking Spotify To Address "Mass Misinformation Events," Take Aim At Joe Rogan's Show|url=https://deadline.com/2022/01/spotify-joe-rogan-doctors-open-letter-1234909702/|url-status=live|access-date=13 January 2022|website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Dickson|first=E. J.|date=12 January 2022|title='A Menace to Public Health': Doctors Demand Spotify Puts an End to Covid Lies on 'Joe Rogan Experience'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/covid-misinformation-joe-rogan-spotify-petition-1282240/|url-status=live|access-date=13 January 2022|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|language=en-US}}</ref>

On 26 January 2022, [[Neil Young]] removed his music from Spotify after they refused to remove the podcast.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yang|first=Maya|date=2022-01-26|title=Spotify removes Neil Young music in feud over Joe Rogan's false Covid claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/jan/26/spotify-neil-young-joe-rogan-covid-misinformation|access-date=2022-01-27|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en}}</ref> [[Joni Mitchell]] subsequently removed her music in support of Young.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/joni-mitchell-spotify-removing-music-joe-rogan-1235166691/ |title=Joni Mitchell Says She's Removing Music From Spotify: 'Irresponsible People Are Spreading Lies' |date=January 28, 2022 |work=Variety |first=Ellise |last=Shafer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Joni Mitchell - News Item|url=https://jonimitchell.com/news/newsitem.cfm?id=1592|access-date=2022-01-30|website=jonimitchell.com}}</ref> Other artists and podcasters, such as [[Nils Lofgren]], [[Brené Brown]] and [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young|Crosby, Stills, & Nash]], also announced a boycott of Spotify.<ref>{{cite web |last=Repko |first=Melissa |title=Bruce Springsteen guitarist Nils Lofgren joins protest of Spotify over Covid misinformation |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/30/bruce-springsteen-guitarist-nils-lofgren-joins-spotify-boycott-.html |website=CNBC |date=30 January 2022 |access-date=30 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Roth |first1=Emma |title=Brené Brown says she won't release new episodes of her Spotify-exclusive podcasts 'until further notice' |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/1/30/22909140/brene-brown-spotify-podcast-joe-rogan-controversy |website=The Verge |date=30 January 2022 |access-date=30 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=David Crosby, Graham Nash and Stephen Stills ask to pull their content from Spotify|language=en|work=NPR|url=https://www.npr.org/2022/02/02/1077653424/crosby-stills-nash-young-spotify|access-date=2022-02-05}}</ref> [[Prince Harry]] and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]], who signed a multi-year partnership with Spotify, said that since April 2021 they had been "expressing concerns" over COVID-19 misinformation on the platform.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/01/30/entertainment/harry-meghan-spotify-misinformation-intl-gbr/index.html|title=Harry and Meghan express 'concerns' to Spotify over misinformation|work=CNN|first1=Max|last1=Foster|first2=Vasco|last2=Cotovio|first3=Rob|last3=Picheta|date=2022-01-30|access-date=2022-01-30}}</ref>

Amid the controversy, as of 28 January 2022 Spotify's stock had fallen 12% week-on-week,<ref>{{cite web|last=Duprey|first=Rich|date=2022-01-28|title=Why Spotify Stock Has Tumbled This Week|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2022/01/28/why-spotify-stock-has-tumbled-this-week/|access-date=2022-01-29|website=The Motley Fool|language=en}}</ref> a loss of $4 billion in [[market capitalization]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Vaziri|first=Aidin|date=2022-01-28|title=Spotify loses $4 billion in market value after Neil Young controversy|access-date=2022-01-30|website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] Datebook|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/music/spotify-loses-4-billion-in-market-value-following-neil-young-controversy}}</ref> By 30 January 2022, this number had grown to a loss of $6.7 billion in market value, a fall of 17% week-on-week, and a fall of 26% year-to-date.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moyer |first1=Liz |title=Spotify to Add Content Advisory to Fight Covid Misinformation Amid Firestorm |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/spotify-to-add-content-advisory-to-fight-covid-misinformation-amid-firestorm-51643577369 |website=Barron's |access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> Spotify's stock fell by 13% after the company reported fourth-quarter earnings on February 2, 2022. Although Ek addressed the Rogan controversy during the earnings call, the loss in value was attributed to the company's guidance on Q1 user growth, which did not meet analyst expectations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=2022-02-02|title=Spotify stock plunges on middling user growth projections|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/02/02/spotify-stock-plunges-on-middling-user-growth-projections.html|access-date=2022-02-04|website=CNBC|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|agency=Reuters|date=February 2, 2022|title=Spotify stocks fall as executives seek to reassure amid Rogan controversy|page=1|work=The Guardian News|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/feb/02/spotify-stocks-fall-rogan-controversy|access-date=February 3, 2022}}</ref>

Spotify promised to add content advisories for anything containing discussions related to COVID-19 and posted additional rules.<ref>{{cite web |last=Roth |first=Emma |title=Spotify finally responds to Joe Rogan controversy with a plan to label podcasts that discuss COVID-19 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/1/30/22909432/spotify-covid-19-moderation-joe-rogan-vaccine-misinformation |website=The Verge |date=30 January 2022 |access-date=30 January 2022}}</ref> Rogan apologized for his role in the controversy, and defended his interviews with two controversial guests, Robert W. Malone and [[Peter A. McCullough]], as "highly credentialed, very intelligent, very accomplished people, and they have an opinion that is different from the mainstream narrative". Rogan said he agreed with Spotify's plan to label episodes including COVID-19 discussions and would try to "have more experts with differing opinions, right after the controversial ones".<ref>{{cite web |last=Byford |first=Sam |title=Joe Rogan defends podcast and apologizes to Spotify for backlash |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/1/31/22910039/joe-rogan-response-neil-young-joni-mitchell-spotify |website=The Verge |date=31 January 2022 |access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref>

In February 2022, Spotify removed about 70 more episodes of ''The Joe Rogan Experience'', reportedly at Rogan's own request.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clark |first1=Mitchell |title=Episodes of Joe Rogan's show are disappearing from Spotify |url=https://www.theverge.com/22918697/joe-rogan-experience-podcast-episodes-disappear-controversy |website=The Verge |date=4 February 2022  |access-date=5 February 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Lucas |title=Joe Rogan Apologizes for Using Racial Slur on His Podcast |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-02-05/joe-rogan-apologizes-for-using-racial-slur-on-his-podcast |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg |date=5 February 2022 |access-date=7 February 2022}}</ref> Musician [[India Arie]] shared a compilation of clips in which Rogan used the "[[Nigger|n word]]" on the podcast, and a clip in which Rogan appears to liken being around black people with the film ''[[Planet of the Apes]]''. Arie announced that she was also boycotting Spotify. Rogan posted an apology, saying it was "regretful and shameful", but said that the clips were "taken out of context".<ref>{{cite web|date=February 5, 2022|title=Joe Rogan apologises for using N-word and racist Planet of the Apes story|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2022/feb/05/joe-rogan-apologises-for-using-n-word-and-racist-planet-of-the-apes-story|work=The Guardian}}</ref>  In a message to employees, Ek said:  "While I strongly condemn what Joe has said and I agree with his decision to remove past episodes from our platform, I realize some will want more. And I want to make one point very clear – I do not believe that silencing Joe is the answer."<ref>{{cite web|date=2022-02-07|title=Spotify CEO says canceling Joe Rogan isn't 'the answer'|url=https://apnews.com/article/spotify-ceo-daniel-ek-joe-rogan-7e0a610a633987f32c9acc3ea14996b6|access-date=2022-02-09|website=AP NEWS|language=en}}</ref>

In July 2022, Crosby, Stills & Nash returned to the platform, although the group's songs with Neil Young were not brought back. The group stated that streaming profits from the newly returned songs will be donated to charities supporting those affected by COVID-19 for "at least a month".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kastrenakes |first1=Jacob |title=Crosby, Stills & Nash return to Spotify after Joe Rogan protest |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/4/23194251/crosby-stills-nash-spotify-return-end-joe-rogan-covid-protest |website=The Verge |date=4 July 2022 |access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref>

